<FIRST>r a AM-DC-10Landing     08-09 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC-10 Landing,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Engine Failure Forces DC-10 To Make Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> DC-10 made an emergency landing Wednesday after the tri-motor jet's No. 2 engine apparently began breaking up and the pilot shut it down, officials said. Flight 308, carrying 256 people from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, landed without incident at <ORGANIZATION> Stapleton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday about 6:30 p.m., according to <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Boulware </PERSON>, a spokesman at the airport. `` They experienced a severe vibration from the No. 2 engine, -LRB- and -RRB- as a precautionary measure, they elected to make an unscheduled landing,'' said <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Whalen </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION>, Minn.-based airline. The No. 2 engine of a DC-10 also is the focus of an investigation into the crash of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> Flight 232 last month in <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, killing 111 of the nearly 300 people aboard. Flight 232's No. 2 engine apparently disintegrated, shooting shrapnel that apparently severed hydraulic lines in the jet, causing almost complete loss of control and forcing the crash-landing at <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s airport. The investigation into the cause of that disaster is continuing. <PERSON> Boulware </PERSON>, who observed the damage to the aircraft after it landed Wednesday night, said there were `` multiple shrapnel-like holes in the outer cowling'' of the No. 2 engine, which on a DC-10 is mounted in the vertical stabilizer at the tail of the aircraft. The other two engines are mounted under the wings. `` One of the holes was big enough I could have stuck by hand through,'' he said. He said the holes were along the upper side of the engine cowling. `` Whatever exited, exited upward,'' he said. He also said a service door on the tail about eight inches square had been blown open, but remained attached to its hinges. <PERSON> Whalen </PERSON> said the landing was normal in terms of controlling the airplane, and the 245 passengers were being placed on alternate flights to <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>. There were 11 crew members on board, he said. <PERSON> Whalen </PERSON> said the airline's mechanics will take a close look at the engine, and since <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> does n't have a maintenance base in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, the jet might have to be shuttled to <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
