<SECOND>PM-APME-FOI,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>FOI Award Finalists Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Six newspapers have been selected as finalists in the annual Freedom of Information Award competition sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Managing Editors Association. The finalists were announced Tuesday by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawpe </PERSON> of The Courier-Journal of <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> APME </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. They are: _ The <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southtown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>, for successful efforts to force release of presentencing letters and reports that a judge said influenced him in sentencing the <LOCATION> Willow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, police chief. _ The <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, for successful efforts to document a city redevelopment project that cost the taxpayers $ 40 million. _ The <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> -RRB- Times-Dispatch, for successful efforts to open juvenile records in the case of the late <PERSON> Rakie </PERSON> <PERSON> Cloyd </PERSON>. _ The <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> -RRB- Mercury News, for efforts to open legislators' driving records and for revealing secret meetings of the state Legislature. _ The Spokesman-Review and <ORGANIZATION> Spokane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, for efforts to obtain records illustrating the problem of sexual abuse of students by teachers. _ The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, for an examination of the way in which corporations and institutions use court secrecy to prevent disclosure of critical information relating to health and safety issues. The winning entry will be announced at the APME convention in October in <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>.
