<SECOND>PM-Japan-Analysis,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kaifu's `Clean Start' Follows False Start by Uno</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Japan, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After a two-month false start, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s governing party is on another `` clean start'' to reform itself. The false start was under <PERSON> Sousuke </PERSON> <PERSON> Uno </PERSON>, who became prime minister June 2 with pledges of political reform but soon was pursued by allegations of having kept paid mistresses. Now another veteran legislator with no personal power base has been pulled up to lead the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. There was an eerie sense of deja vu in <PERSON> Toshiki </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON>'s acceptance remarks If he had Uno's glasses and streak of white hair, it would have been hard to discern that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> had a new leader. Uno was clear of involvement in the Recruit influence-buying scandal that caused his predecessor, <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>, to leave office prematurely. <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON> bears the minor taint of receiving the equivalent of $ 110,000 in donations from <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> over five years, but he did not receive profits from cut-price stock deals, as did most of the party leaders now sidelined. That scandal, <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> said on June 2, `` has had a dramatic effect on our party. I would like to take this opportunity to reflect on this development so we can make a clean start in politics and regain the confidence of our people.'' <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON> said Tuesday, after winning the party presidency, that it was `` a crucial time.'' He called for debate through which `` we can gain the people's understanding of our policies.'' `` I want to carry out reforms and pass reform legislation based on our deep self-reflection,'' he said. `` We must carry out political reforms and shed our old skin.'' Like Uno and <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>, and almost everyone else in his conservative party, <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON> said the Liberal Democrats were in a crisis. The crisis appears deeper than ever, and the calendar is moving steadily toward the next encounter with the electorate. In elections July 23, the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> lost constrol of Parliament's upper house for the first time in the party's 34-year history. Elections for all seats in the lower house must be called by July 1990, but the Socialist-led opposition in the upper chamber will try to create a legislative deadlock to make the government hold them sooner. So low is the Liberal Democrats' popularity that analysts expect they would lose their majority in the lower house. The reasons are many, and not easy to overcome. Despite a pledge not to impose a new major tax, the governing party bulldozed a 3 percent sales tax through <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. When it was coupled with reductions in personal income and inheritance taxes, the net effect was a reduction in the average household's tax burden, but the sales tax remains unpopular. It also produces 10 percent of government revenue, which makes abolishing it expensive. Although the Recruit scandal ended officially in April with the indictment of two legislators on bribe-taking charges, it lives on in the minds of many who feel party leaders should not have escaped prosecution. Among those who did was <PERSON> Yasuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON>, who preceded <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> as prime minister. The easy money politicians reaped from the <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> was spread so widely that nearly all top Liberal Democratic figures were tainted, making it impossible for them to succeed <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> or Uno. They remain powerful, however, and voters know many hope for future high office. To the sales tax and Recruit scandal, which created an image of arrogance and unaccountability, was added the insult to women of Uno's alleged affairs. The result was the thrashing the Liberal Democrats took in the July 23 election. <PERSON> Takako </PERSON> <PERSON> Doi </PERSON>, the first woman to lead a party in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, is popular and has been able to fuzz over her <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s policy of an unarmed, neutral <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, which is not the majority opinion. She attacks the sales tax and the governing party's image. <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON> is new and untried. He is 58, still boyish-looking, young enough in Japanese politics to suggest a new generation and has reform credentials from service under <PERSON> Takeo </PERSON> <PERSON> Miki </PERSON>, a `` Mr. Clean'' prime minister of the 1970s. He has until October, when the party votes again on its president, to show he has made a good start on rescuing the deeply troubled party. If he does n't, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> could be looking for its fourth prime minister of 1989.
</TEXT>
