<FIRST>r a PM-PieFight     08-09 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pie Fight,0710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Owners of Restaurant Fight for Slice of Pie Business</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LR1 of Aug. 8.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FREEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The pies lining the two shelves behind the counter at the Club Cafe have always been in demand. Now, they're in court. When <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> McNanna </PERSON> bought 51 percent of the cafe in May, he thought he was buying the restaurant's award-winning recipes, too. But then the baker _ <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, a former part-owner who had the recipes in her head _ quit and <PERSON> McNanna </PERSON> sued to get the recipes back. `` They're not written down someplace,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> `` The recipes are something my client has developed over many years.'' Attorneys still are taking depositions and will request a final hearing in a month or so in chancery court to determine ownership of the recipes, <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> said. In the meantime, the 45-year-old Club Cafe still offers, for $ 1 a slice, 14 varieties of pies: peanut butter, chocolate, coconut, banana, lemon, pineapple, egg custard, pecan, apple, Dutch apple, cherry, blueberry, banana split and strawberry. And four cheesecakes. <PERSON> McNanna </PERSON> says the pies these days are every bit as good as Mrs. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>'s, and his baker, <PERSON> Ricky </PERSON> <PERSON> West </PERSON>, a 14-year veteran at the restaurant, agrees. `` The pies, we have it down to an art,'' <PERSON> McNanna </PERSON> said. `` Just right after she quit, we had it down pretty close.'' The customers? `` They ca n't tell the difference,'' <PERSON> West </PERSON> said. But some say they can. `` My opinion is that the crust is n't as good,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, an administrative assistant for a judge who's been a regular at the cafe for about five years. `` If you've had the way the pies used to be, you know what's genuine and what's imitation,'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said `` We true Hot Springs natives could brag that we had the best pies in <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>.'' Businessman <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> has been indulging in Club Cafe pies since he was a teen-ager 30 years ago, when he was known as the `` Dutch Apple Kid.'' <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> said he could n't quite put his finger on the difference. `` It seems like it's not quite up to what it used to be,'' he said. `` But they're still good pies.'' <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON>, 19, who used to help out at the restaurant when her mother worked there, said she ca n't taste any difference and she's sampled everything on the pie menu. `` They taste the same to me. The meringue has a different texture, but the fillings are the same,'' she said. <PERSON> West </PERSON> said he cranks out 50 to 70 pies a day, a job he calls more stressful than his old duty of cooking the main meals. The chocolate pie, one of several crowned with 3 inches of meringue, is his customers' favorite, with coconut next, he said. Under a temporary restraining order issued in May, Mrs. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> has been barred from the Club Cafe premises and is working as a waitress at a local Oriental restaurant. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> said there are no orders preventing her from baking elsewhere. Mrs. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> filed a counterclaim in June asking that the sale of the 51 percent share to <PERSON> McNanna </PERSON> be rescinded because of a dispute over payment on a $ 40,000 banknote for her mother and aunt, who each owned a 20 percent share in the cafe. Mrs. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> had owned the remaining 11 percent sold to <PERSON> McNanna </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>'s husband, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, still owns 29 percent of the restaurant and <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> owns the remaining 20 percent. <PERSON> Monty </PERSON> <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>, owner of <ORGANIZATION> Monty </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pawn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shop </ORGANIZATION>, said he's gone into the cafe just about every day since 1954 and has seen a lot of changes, though the same faded red-and-white `` Club Cafe'' sign still hangs over the door. `` Five to six years ago, you could come here for lunch and there'd be a line out the door,'' <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> said. But until the last couple of months, that was n't the case anymore, he said. `` There are lots of new faces,'' <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> said. `` More tourists seem to be coming in here.'' `` It's kind of funny, getting all the publicity,'' <PERSON> West </PERSON> said.
