<HEAD>Groups Say Staff Wanted Books Purchased in Lieu of Speaking Fees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal grand jury wants to examine documents from at least three groups that bought hundreds of copies of a book by former <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> instead of paying him a speaking fee, the groups say. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> refused Tuesday to discuss the grand jury probe. But lawyers for <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> confirmed they received subpoenas requesting documents related to the book. A spokesman for Ocean Spray, a cranberry and citrus growers cooperative in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, said the grand jury also was seeking documents from his group. Company spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawlor </PERSON> would n't discuss details of the subpoena, but he did say the group bought $ 2,000 worth of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s book for <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s use <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> resigned this summer after the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> ethics committee accused him of trying to evade <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> limits on outside income through bulk sales of `` Reflections of a Public Man.'' He earned royalties of 55 percent on the book's sales. The House limits members' earnings from speaking engagements to 30 percent of the congressional salary, but royalties are exempt. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> said the investigation appeared to be `` very routine.'' <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said the agency's inquiry is continuing `` I ca n't comment on any aspect of the investigation, except I will confirm that it is ongoing,'' he said. <PERSON> Lawlor </PERSON> said <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> spoke to Ocean Spray growers and management employees in November 1985. He said <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s staff suggested that instead of giving the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> speaker an honorarium, the cooperative could use the money to buy the books. `` As far as we were concerned, it was an honorarium in the form of a book purchase in place of a cash honorarium,'' <PERSON> Lawlor </PERSON> said. `` How he was to use them -LRB- the books -RRB- was for him to determine.'' <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Fly </PERSON>, a lawyer for <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said the school received a subpoena for documents relating to <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s 1984 speech there and the subsequent purchase of $ 3,000 worth of books Fly said the university had agreed to pay <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> $ 3,000. However, a <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> aide called after the speech to say the speaker had reached his limit on outside income and asked if he could use the money to buy copies of his book for the university, Fly said. `` We received about 504 copies of that book,'' Fly said. <PERSON> Laurene </PERSON> <PERSON> Janik </PERSON>, general counsel for the Realtors organization, said <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> spoke to the group in April 1985. A $ 2,000 check was issued and voided, and the money was to be used to buy <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s book, she said However, the Realtors have no record of receiving copies of the book, Ms. <PERSON> Janik </PERSON> said.
