<HEAD>Sugar Industry Stockpiling Ammunition for Quota Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s sugar industry is stockpiling statistics to throw into the fight to maintain import quotas that ward off foreign sugar and boost consumer prices at home. An industry study unveiled Tuesday said the sugar and allied corn-sweetener industries directly create 144,442 full-time jobs nationwide and pump almost $ 7.4 billion a year into the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy. `` It shows there is a lot more to this industry than the attacks that say it only benefits a handful of growers,'' <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> Markwart </PERSON> said in making the study public. <PERSON> Markwart </PERSON> cited findings that, counting indirect effects, sugar and sweetener production generate $ 18.5 billion in wages and revenues, plus 361,000 jobs annually in 42 states. If there is a move to lift quotas as part of the 1990 farm bill, the survey is guaranteed to be used by the industry to offset claims that it represents only a narrow special interest. Because of the quotas, a pound of raw sugar that sells for 14 cents in world markets goes for about 24 cents in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. That difference is passed on to consumers after the sugar is processed, packaged and sent to the grocery shelf. Consumer groups and industries such as soft drink and candy makers complain about the high cost of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sugar. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Agriculture Committees, however, have left the quotas intact. The two panels include members from major sugar-growing states and lawmakers reap hefty campaign contributions from growers. The survey also takes into account jobs and earnings generated by the corn-sweetener industry. Its products, used widely in soft drinks and various foods, trail sugar in price and the two industries are often allies. Lifting quotas would eventually scuttle not only beet and cane growers but sweetener manufacturing in this country, <PERSON> Markwart </PERSON> said. The survey said annual sugar and sweetener output totaling more than $ 7.3 billion a year is spread over many states. It said that the combined value topped $ 100 million in 17 states. The major corn states of <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> headed the list of 17. Those two states, plus <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, were the leading corn-sweetener producers. Major cane states were <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> made the list principally as a refining site. Also among the 17 were the sugarbeet producing states of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>. Among states on the list, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> was notable for its diversified production. In employment, the agricultural side of the two industries contributes 115,268 jobs and the processing side 29,173, according to the study. It cited seven states with substantially higher employment totals than others: <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, 11,057; <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, 10,513; <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, 9,929; <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, 9,890; <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, 9,731; <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, 8,907; and <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, 8,889. The total includes farm workers involved in growing corn, even though economists are n't sure just what would happen to those jobs if sweetener production in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> halted. But the study said that, leaving out corn production, overall employment in the industries would total `` a highly creditable 75,411 full-time positions.'' Agricultural wages for corn and sugar totaled more than $ 1.2 billion nationwide, according to the study. Cane states had the highest overall payrolls, $ 159 million for <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and $ 82.7 million for <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>. On the processing side, wages came to more than $ 811 million. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> led the way with $ 118.5 million. Overall wages for growing and processing nationwide were just over $ 2 billion, the survey said. It said that sugar and sweetener business generates wages of $ 100 million a year or more in eight states: <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>. Sugar industry critics are quick to point out not only the impact of quotas on the wallets of consumers but the other side of the employment story. `` <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> workers also do not escape the adverse effects of this program,'' Sen. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> recently. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, the program's leading <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> critic, noted that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> refineries have been closing their doors and laying off workers because of high sugar prices. He said those costs are also hurting other industries. `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> food and beverage manufacturing industries employ hundreds of thousands of people,'' he said. `` The chocolate and confectionary industries alone employ more than 60,000 people. These jobs are threatened by competition from foreign manufacturers who have access to sugar at world market prices, not <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s inflated price.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farm machinery sales are expected to rise for the third year in a row, increasing from $ 6 billion in 1988 to as much as $ 6.7 billion in 1989, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Higher net cash incomes, lower real interest rates, rising farmland values and lowered agricultural debt are all trends that are contributing to expectations for a better year in tractor sales, <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> said. It said demand for the more powerful tractors is especially strong thus far in 1989. Sales of 139-plus horsepower, two-wheel drive and four-wheel drive tractors are expected to climb 23 percent and 65 percent respectively.
