<HEAD>HUD Officials Can't Find Files of Former Assistant Secretary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> says it ca n't locate the files of a former housing official whose conduct is under scrutiny in the influence-peddling probe, but the former official says he does n't have them. `` I do n't even know where they are kept, much less take them with me,'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> said Tuesday, adding that he took no files when he left <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> last year. `` I do n't have them.'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Lafferty </PERSON>, deputy assistant secretary for public affairs at <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` He may have taken them with him _ we do n't have them here.'' However, he said the department has no evidence that <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> took the files. `` They could be someplace that we do n't now know about but they are not in the typical places that you would look for them,'' <PERSON> Lafferty </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials realized the files were missing after receiving a Freedom of Information Act request for access to them. The files of two other former <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials _ Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and his top aide <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> _ have provided dramatic insight into their activities at the agency. <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in May that he had no direct role in funding decisions. Since then, however, a number of news accounts have detailed <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s personal intervention in several <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> projects, and his files offer further evidence that he was more involved in some decisions than he indicated in his congressional testimony. Ms. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>'s files show that she was often contacted by developers and consultants seeking <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> approval for projects and often gave proposals her endorsement although her job carried no official funding authority. For two years <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> was <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s assistant secretary for housing, a powerful position that has jurisdiction over many of <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s subsidy programs The report that sparked the congressional and internal investigations of <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> focused heavily on <PERSON> Demery </PERSON>'s conduct. That report, by <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s inspector general, questioned the selection process used to award lucrative rehabilitation subsidies and said many of those who benefited were contributors to a charity <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> helped establish. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> Inspector General <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> concluded that <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> committed no criminal offenses but said that prominent Republicans and former agency officials appeared to get special treatment from <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which reviewed the report to determine whether <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> violated <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s standards of conduct, said last month it would not prosecute him. <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> also was in charge of another program that was the subject of a critical audit by the inspector general. That report said <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> awarded emergency <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> funding to a number of projects that were n't eligible. Several qualified projects that did n't receive funding later went under and were taken over by the government, the report said. An <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> review of the program found that developers of projects that got emergency funding although auditors said they did n't qualify included a former business associate and several donors to his pet charity. <PERSON> Demery </PERSON>, in a recent interview, said he made the awards `` on the merits'' and questioned the audit's assertion that many of the projects were n't eligible.
