<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As many as 14 million families could be forced into homelessness by a mild recession in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy, according to a study. The report by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affordable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said public efforts to help the homeless rely are badly underfinanced, uncoordinated and are conducted by officials often unaware of the resources available to them. The report by the institute, a research center at <ORGANIZATION> Rutgers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, estimated that there are 4 million to 14 million American families `` living on the knife edge of homelessness'' who could face life on the streets should a mild recession occur. `` They are one pay check, one domestic argument from the streets,'' the report said. `` In a mild recession, homelessness in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is likely to double and triple almost overnight.'' Estimates on the current number of homeless people range between 655,000 to 4 million, but the total is growing 20 percent to 40 percent annually, the study said.
