<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The withdrawal of his sole opponent leaves the way clear for former Mayor <PERSON> Maynard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> to return to City Hall for a third term. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Lomax </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Fulton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, withdrew from the mayoral election Tuesday after polls showed he was far behind. That left the 51-year-old <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who served two four-year terms beginning in 1974, with no opposition. <PERSON> Lomax </PERSON>, 41, who trailed by 34 percentage points in the polls, said he was stepping aside to ensure `` this campaign does not divide our city's family.'' He might have been able to win, <PERSON> Lomax </PERSON> said, by hitting harder on crime, but `` the real casualty of that attack ... would have been the city ... It would have been too costly a victory.'' The rate of 176 crimes per 1,000 residents in this city of 445,000 is the nation's worst, according to <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> statistics released Monday. There are no other candidates; and if one announced, there would n't be enough time before the Oct. 3 election to mount a credible campaign, said <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> pollster <PERSON> Claibourne </PERSON> <PERSON> Darden </PERSON>. `` There's no time, no body and no money,'' <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> said. `` You've got three no's. City Councilman <PERSON> Hosea </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> hinted he might run simply to give <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> some opposition. `` It would be a tragedy to see <PERSON> Maynard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> walk into City Hall. He ought to be challenged,'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, like <PERSON> Lomax </PERSON> a black Democrat, had cemented his populist appeal among the black majority with growing support from white businessmen. <PERSON> Lomax </PERSON> ran as the more business-oriented candidate but failed to broaden his support. During his terms, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> had often battled with businessmen, who have gotten along well with outgoing Mayor <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>. `` There has been a change in attitudes. And a lot of the old guard is gone,'' said <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuster </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s press secretary. <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Lomax </PERSON> ads, in which he tried to link <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> with <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s crime rate, probably had little impact and forced <PERSON> Lomax </PERSON> to drain his coffers. `` He took that high-risk technique of viciously attacking his opponent, and he found out why it's a high-risk strategy _ it does n't work most of the time,'' <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> said. `` That's the most important thing. He's broke.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, whose campaign featured a pledge not to allow a building boom to overrun neighborhoods, said the negative ads `` had very little effect on me.'' <PERSON> Lomax </PERSON>'s withdrawal allows him to keep his job as commission chairman, which he would have been forced to give up by the Aug. 16 qualifying deadline. <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> includes about 90 percent of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s population, which is 61 percent black. Young, who can not seek a third consecutive term, said <PERSON> Lomax </PERSON>'s decision to pull out `` probably relieves a lot of friends of both of them. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> claimed that <PERSON> Lomax </PERSON>, who worked for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in his previous administrations, always intended to drop out to prevent a candidate from running who was unacceptable to the `` black middle-class power structure.'' `` I have said from the beginning _ <PERSON> Maynard </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lomax </PERSON> would never face each other. This was only a political drama,''