<HEAD>Church Regains Possession of Byzantine Mosaics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JODI PERRAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A priest blessed four sixth-century mosaics in a basement vault, where they will stay while an art collector appeals a court ruling giving the <ORGANIZATION> Greek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orthodox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> possession of the rare Byzantine works. The Rev. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Rousakis </PERSON>, pastor of Holy Trinity Greek Orthodox Church in <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>, read from a prayer book and sang in Greek over the artworks lying on the basement vault's floor Tuesday. He sprinkled them with holy water, then he and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyprianou </PERSON>, senior counsel for the Republic of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, knelt and kissed each one. `` In the orthodox faith, the mosaics are sacred, a consecrated form of art that is part and parcel of our worship service. Once they are removed, it's almost as if they're stained or tainted. They have to be restored,'' <PERSON> Rousakis </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Noland </PERSON> ruled Thursday that art dealer <PERSON> Peg </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> of suburban <LOCATION> Carmel </LOCATION> had not obtained legal title to the mosaics when she purchased them for $ 1.2 million last summer in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> from <PERSON> Aydin </PERSON> <PERSON> Dikmen </PERSON>, a Turk living in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The Republic of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> and the church sued Ms. <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> last spring to recover the works, which had been stripped from a church in Turkish-occupied northern <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> in 1979. <PERSON> Noland </PERSON> ordered the mosaics returned to the Cypriots. Attorneys for both sides agreed Tuesday the artworks would be turned over to the Cypriots but must remain in the <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> vault pending appeals. They may be removed only under a court order or agreement by both sides. `` Today is a great day for <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Kyprianou </PERSON>. `` Years of hard work in securing our artifacts, our cultural heritage, have not been wasted.'' Tuesday's prayers included one of forgiveness for <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> and those who took the mosaics from the church and smuggled them out of the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> island nation. `` We have learned to forgive people,'' <PERSON> Kyprianou </PERSON> said. `` What we wanted are our mosaics back.'' The mosaics, pieced together with painted glass about 525 A.D., are fragments of a much larger work on the ceiling of a church in northern <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. The images of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> as a boy, the apostles <PERSON> James </PERSON> and <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> and an archangel are among only a handful of icons surviving the first centuries of Christianity. Under Tuesday's agreement, <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> controls the keys to the vault but will not move the mosaics or restore them during the appeals process unless <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> agrees. She must file an appeal of <PERSON> Noland </PERSON>'s decision within 14 days and must not seek delays during the appeals process. `` We very strongly intend to appeal. I just simply totally disagree with the decision,'' Ms. <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said.
