<SECOND>PM-California Quake,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Geologists Warn of Bigger Quakes After 5.2 Temblor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An earthquake that broke windows and contributed to one death in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> area could herald even stronger temblors along the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Andreas </LOCATION> fault, scientists say. `` The stress is building up in the earth and we're going to start getting large earthquakes,'' said <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, a geophysicist with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Geological Survey in <LOCATION> Menlo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>. `` It should serve as a reminder to prepare.'' The quake rolled for 10 seconds, shaking buildings and awakening residents but causing only minor damage, authorities said. `` I thought all my windows were going to break,'' said <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunlap </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. `` My whole bed was shaking.'' It struck at 1:13 a.m. about 50 miles south of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and had a magnitude of 5.2 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale, according to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Geological Survey. It was centered on the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Andreas </LOCATION> fault about 15 miles south of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>. State earthquake experts and the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> issued a warning of increased risk and said another quake as high as 6.2 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale could strike <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> in the next five days. `` It certainly shows us the fault is becoming more active,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, who added that the quake was the largest in the area since 1969. Geologists said the chances of a bigger quake in the same spot diminished with each passing hour, however. The quake occurred as state and federal emergency services officials prepared to conduct a two-day test of their response to a catastrophic earthquake. <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, wife of Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, was in <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> to attend the first day of the test. When she woke up at 5:30 a.m. and saw coverage of the actual earthquake on television, she thought it was part of the exercise. `` I thought, ` Gee, this is pretty interesting. They have the simulation on television already,''' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gatos </LOCATION>, where the quake was centered, police reported that 19-year-old <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bignall </PERSON> jumped from his bedroom window after apparently being startled awake by the earthquake. <PERSON> Bignall </PERSON> died of multiple traumatic injuries, according to a spokeswoman with the <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> coroner's office. His half-brother said <PERSON> Bignall </PERSON> had never experienced an earthquake. `` My brother was a sound sleeper,'' said <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Burger </PERSON>, who shared the apartment with <PERSON> Bignall </PERSON>. `` And I think the motion of the quake seemed so violent and disorienting that he just leaped out the window. He felt he had to get out, and I do n't think he knew what he was doing.'' Residents reported some broken windows and items falling off shelves but no major problems, a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gatos </LOCATION> police dispatcher said. Damage was confined mostly to <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clara </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cruz </LOCATION> counties, according to the state <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>. The quake was felt as far away as <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Luis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Obispo </LOCATION>, about 230 miles south of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. Residents of <LOCATION> Sonoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, 60 miles to the north, also felt the temblor, according to the state agency. A moderate aftershock measuring 4.2 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale struck at 1:44 a.m., followed by a second, stronger aftershock that measured 4.5 at 8:53 a.m., the <ORGANIZATION> USGS </ORGANIZATION> said. The open-ended <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale is a measure of ground motion recorded on a seismograph. Each increase of one number means a tenfold increase in ground motion. An earthquake of 3.5 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale can cause slight damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6 severe damage. A 7 reading is a `` major'' earthquake, capable of widespread heavy damage; 8 is a `` great'' quake, capable of tremendous damage. The <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> earthquake of 1906, which occurred before the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale was devised, has been estimated at 8.3 on the scale.
