<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One man died after a rocket hit an ammunition dump, triggering explosions that lasted more than 3 -LCB- hours, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sources said today. Relief workers said eight people were injured. The man, who lived about 500 yards from the dump in the <LOCATION> Khair </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Khana </LOCATION> district of northwest <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, was running from his house after the rocket hit at dusk Tuesday and ammunition and rockets in the dump started to explode, said the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabi </PERSON> <PERSON> Amani </PERSON> said he expected to have information on the death later today. The Avicina emergency hospital, which acts as a coordinating center for casualties, reported five Tuesday after the dump started exploding. But today, doctors there said they knew of no dead or injured and that casualties might have been taken to military hospitals. Relief workers, speaking on condition of anonymity, said eight people suffered serious injuries in rocket attacks citywide Tuesday night, some in the <LOCATION> Khair </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Khana </LOCATION> district. After intense rocket attacks on <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> for four days, the city had been relatively quiet until about half a dozen rockets hit the hillside dump. Clouds of black smoke billowed over the northwestern part of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, flames danced in the night sky and explosions boomed across the city, several rocking buildings. At one point, all the lights in the city went out for 20 minutes in a power outage. But this morning the <PERSON> Khair </PERSON> <PERSON> Khana </PERSON> district was bustling again, including the streets just below the hillside dump, which looked like a burned field. In some houses the windows were broken and the floors were covered with as