nt can not look the other way while violence, often drug-related, ravages many of our inner-city communities and subjects innocent citizens to the cross-fire of turf wars between urban terrorist gangs,'' <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s crime package focused on increasing the penalties for the criminal use of guns, ending plea bargaining in such cases, hiring more investigators and prosecutors and doubling the space in federal prisons, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said. `` Such a comprehensive approach, if replicated at the state and local level, can go a long way toward restoring much-needed credibility to the deterrent capacity of our criminal justice system,'' he said. Regarding drug use and trafficking in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said the only way to win the `` war on drugs'' was to `` re-establish the values that make a drug-dependent lifestyle an inadmissible option in this great nation.'' He praised the military's mandatory drug testing program, saying it reduced the incidence of drug use from 27 percent in 1980 to 4.8 percent last year. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> urged more drug testing of American workers. Speaking to reporters after the speech, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s validation of drug-testing meant private and public-sector employers could begin `` reasonable'' drug-testing progams. `` I think private employers should examine the appropriateness of it in the workplace,'' he said.
