<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> organizer of underground tests of an experimental AIDS drug says he will accept a government invitation to discuss bringing the trials into the open. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON>, co-director of the AIDS education group <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inform </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday that he found the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s offer to discuss sanctioning the trials a positive development. `` We have said from the beginning we would like to do this in the open,'' <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON> said. The clandestine trial began in April when the drug began to be viewed by AIDS patients as a last hope. <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON> said he and others started the unauthorized testing to find out whether it worked before its uncontrolled use became widespread. Going through the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> would have taken too long, he said, but he also has said that he and others kept the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> apprised of the study. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> began investigating the underground trials of Compound Q in June after a patient died and two others had adverse reactions. <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON> said it was unclear whether Compound Q was related to the death. Compound Q is a protein from the root of a cucumber-like plant that has been used for centuries in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to induce abortions and treat certain tumors. <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON>'s group smuggled the drug into the country with the help of couriers. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> told <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON> in a letter he received Tuesday to stop the trials, but offered to talk about conforming them to <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> regulations. `` While we can not condone the unapproved administration of trichosanthin -LRB- Compound Q -RRB-, we share your belief that important drug evaluation information may be generated by community-based organizations,'' said the letter, signed by <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peck </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evaluation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>. `` We therefore want to meet with you, and with other concerned parties, just as soon as possible, to discuss the possibility of your participation in a community-based trial ... that complies with existing law and regulations,'' the letter said. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> has come to rely increasingly on community-based trials, a concept pioneered by AIDS activists in which local physicians administer experimental therapies to AIDS patients and keep detailed records as part of a safety and efficacy study. The underground study of 42 patients is nearly completed. Treatments with the drug have finished and analysis of the data is expected to be completed within the month, <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON> said. `` We will have enough data to make a reliable judgment to know whether this is a big deal'' and worth further testing, he said. `` After that everybody at <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> is going to have to scratch their heads and ask why it takes 3 -LCB- years under normal -LRB- FDA-approved -RRB- circumstances'' to make the same determination. If the drug is worth testing further, <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON> said he and others would bring the data to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and talk to <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> officials about opening FDA-sanctioned, community-based clinical trials. The only approved clinical trial of the drug for AIDS patients is being conducted at <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. A highly purified form of trichosanthin developed at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Genelabs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Redwood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> is being used in that trial. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> says its procedure for approving drugs, including several levels of clinical trials, is designed to determine reliably the safety and effectiveness of a drug as well as to protect those who volunteer to participate.
</TEXT>
