<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Non-Estonian factory and transit workers went on strike today in the Estonian capital to protest a new law adopted with nationalist support to tighten residency requirements for elections. `` The strike is against yesterday's decision, which the workers consider discriminatory,'' said <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> <PERSON> Kogan </PERSON>, an ethnic <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> and leader of Inter-movement. The group is championing the interests of Russians and other non-Estonians in this small Baltic republic. The law passed Tuesday by the republic's Supreme Soviet, or parliament, requires residents to live in their district for two years or anywhere in <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> for five years before they are allowed to vote. Candidates for elective office must live in the same place for five years or in <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> for 10 years. The official Soviet news agency, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, said workers in <LOCATION> Tallinn </LOCATION> were not unloading freight trains or airplanes and that some auto transport workers also were on strike. Air freight was paralyzed, it said. <PERSON> Kogan </PERSON>, speaking in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Tallinn </LOCATION>, said the Elamo construction enterprise, the Dvigatel motor works, and the <PERSON> Kalinin </PERSON> electronics plant were on strike. He said workers had struck at least 17 sites, but he could not give a figure for how many people had walked off their jobs. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said workers at 19 sites were on strike. Ethnic Estonians make up slightly more than 60 percent of the population and pushed the law to protect themselves from an influx of other nationalities. But Russians, who make up about a third of <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>'s 1.6 million people, charge that the law discriminates against non-Estonians because they tend to be more recent arrivals. `` The law guarantees general voting rights to practically all citizens of Estonian nationality and deprives tens of thousands of people of other nationalities,'' the government daily <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> quoted a deputy identified as <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lukoshkin </PERSON> telling the Estonian Supreme Soviet on Tuesday. Non-Estonian workers conducted a warning strike in late July but ended it when the government agreed to form a commission to look into their complaints. Now, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said, the strikers want the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> to set up a commission to look broadly into <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>'s drive for greater local control. <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> has adopted a series of measures to increase its local autonomy and protect ethnic Estonians. The republic has won approval from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to launch a new economic policy that Estonian leaders say will even allow the republic to issue its own currency.
