<HEAD>Non-Estonians Walk Off Jobs to Protest Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Non-Estonian factory and transit workers walked off their jobs in the Estonian capital of <LOCATION> Tallinn </LOCATION> on Wednesday to protest a new law that tightens residency requirements for voting and holding elected office. `` The strike is against yesterday's decision, which the workers consider discriminatory,'' said <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> <PERSON> Kogan </PERSON>, an ethnic Russian and leader of the InterMovement group that is pushing the interests of Russians and other non-Estonians in the Baltic republic. `` I'm concerned about my children and grandchildren,'' said <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Chugunov </PERSON>, 42, one of those on strike at the <PERSON> Kalinin </PERSON> electronics factory. `` They started with a language law, and then it's something else, and et cetera, et cetera, et cetera,'' said <PERSON> Chugunov </PERSON>, a 33-year-resident of <LOCATION> Tallinn </LOCATION>, who wo n't be affected by the tighter residency requirements. The strikers sent a committee of four to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to seek a meeting with Vice President <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lukyanov </PERSON>, <PERSON> Chugunov </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Chugunov </PERSON>, a member of the strike committee, said thousands of workers were on strike at 20 enterprises in <LOCATION> Tallinn </LOCATION> and two in <LOCATION> Kokhtla-Jarve </LOCATION>, an industrial city east of <LOCATION> Tallinn </LOCATION>. He could not give the total number of strikers, but he said that at some of the largest factories, 3,000 or more workers were off the job. Pickets blocked the entrances to the factories. <PERSON> Kogan </PERSON>, a deputy to the national <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputies parliament, said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Tallinn </LOCATION> that in addition the Elamo construction enterprise, the Dvigat