<HEAD>Doctors Say Maggot Treatment Rare, But Effective</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATTY REINERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Though many people have a strong aversion to maggots, the parents of a 17-year-old girl say the centuries-old practice of allowing the fly larvae to eat decaying human tissue may have saved their daughter's legs. `` My husband said, ` Let's go for it,' and <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> said ` Let's go for it,' so we did and it worked,'' <PERSON> Patsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dillingham </PERSON>, the patient's mother, said Tuesday <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> <PERSON> Dillingham </PERSON> became critically ill suddenly on May 10 and was taken from a clinic to <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> the next day. Doctors there diagnosed her illness as <LOCATION> meningococcemia </LOCATION>, a blood-borne bacterial infection that caused heart failure, kidney problems and diseased skin, and eventually led to the amputation of part of one leg and the toes on the other foot. Dr. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Fields </PERSON> of the hospital staff said antibiotics used to kill the bacteria released a powerful toxin in <PERSON> Dillingham </PERSON>'s circulatory system that caused blood clots, reducing the flow of blood to her legs Meanwhile, the bacteria continued its direct attack on her skin, rotting it from the inside out, said her father, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Dillingham </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Poolesville </LOCATION> town commissioner. Once <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON>'s doctors amputated her left leg below the knee and her toes on the right foot, they still were faced with cleaning the remaining skin so skin grafts could be done. Antibiotics did not work fast enough and paring the skin from her legs did not work well enough, her doctors said. `` With <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON>'s tissue dying, they needed to do something,'' said <PERSON> Patsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dillingham </PERSON>. `` When they use surgery, they take the live tissue as well as the dead tissue, and they had taken so much that they wanted to avoid that at all cost. All of her skin from the waist down was dying.'' After a long search by the hospital and the Dillinghams, more than 1,500 fly larvae were located in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. On July 21, <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> watched as the insects, so tiny she could barely seem them, were released onto her legs and secured with tape. `` At first, they tickled when they put them in. My nurse and I were laughing,'' she said. `` I could feel them moving everywhere.'' After 36 hours, doctors used a high-pressure hose to wash them away. By then, the maggots had grown from less than one-sixteenth inch in diameter to nearly as big around as the end of a little finger, her father said. `` It's a gruesome issue, but we know that it can work,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Provost </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dermatology </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's clinically well-known that maggots will eat the dead tissue while leaving healthy tissue intact.'' Maggots have been used for centuries to remove dead tissue from infected wounds, said Dr. <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Howell </PERSON>, assistant professor of internal medicine and history at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON>. `` When you have an infected wound, you'd rather have an animal, like a maggot, eat it up rather than letting -LRB- the infectious tissue -RRB- stay there,'' <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> said. `` It was probably used more before antibiotics, or when it was more difficult for people to get to surgery.'' Although the treatment has been used in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since at least the Civil War, <PERSON> Provost </PERSON> said it has been used in modern times only as a last resort because of people's aversion to the maggots. `` It is really horrendous,'' Provost said, `` and most physicians are reluctant to do it because it tends to be sensationalized.'' But <PERSON> Dillingham </PERSON>, a former teacher of biology, physiology and anatomy, was familiar with the cleaning capabilities of the insects and encouraged his daughter to try it. `` I just wanted to get out of the hospital,'' said <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON>, who is senior class president and a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Poolsville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Junior-Senior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> track team. `` If the maggots meant I could get out sooner, then I wanted them to use them.'' <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON>'s doctors are optimistic she will walk again with protheses. `` The grafts have taken a hundred percent,'' her mother said. `` We're on the home stretch now.''
