 Civil rights leaders said Wednesday it was kind of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to come talk at their conference, but one added that it's now time to `` dance with me, Prexy.'' `` We set the clock yesterday when he started talking and we will run it until we get here next year,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters at a news conference winding up a four-day convention here. The Rev. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, struck a similar note in a concluding address. `` We heard Mr. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> say the right words. Now he must turn on the music and dance with me, Prexy,'' he told delegates. `` Yesterday's meeting with the president would have been a lot different if he had some dependency on African American voters,'' <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> said. `` The truth of the matter is that <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was being kind when he came here yesterday. We did n't elect him and he knew that.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in his speech committed his administration to combatting discrimination, but some delegates expressed disappointment that he did not comment on recent <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions that have eroded affirmative action. `` We must call the administration to sacrament,'' said <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON>. `` We must call it to deal realistically with the terrible problems we face today.'' <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> said he believes Republicans are making modest inroads among black voters, but added, `` If the Republicans are really serious about attracting <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION>, they need to get some programs that deal with the problems, concerns and aspirations of the African American community.'' He said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was the first president to participate in a national Urban League conference in a non-election year since <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> in 1977. `` This president has at least said that he is willing to debate the issues and work with us,'' the Urban League president said. <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> said he believed the conference made headway in dealing with the issue of drugs, which was high on its agenda. `` I think this conference has made a major contribution through raising the consciousness level,'' he said, `` but also putting this organization on record as being at least one national organization that is African American that has publicly stated that it intends to wage war on drugs.'' <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> said it was up to the government to stop drugs at the border and provide drug treatment programs, but, `` We can, in our own neighborhoods, help put the pushers in jail.''
