<HEAD>Burma Announces New Military Courts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s military government has set up more regional military courts and extended martial law powers to junior army commanders, according to an official Burmese report. The report, issued Tuesday, came on the first anniversary of the beginning of a natiowide uprising for democracy, which Gen. Saw <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> crushed in September after he took power. A July 18 order empowered the commanders of the <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> region and northwestern and central areas to establish military courts to try martial law violators. These were already put into effect in the capital, <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>. The new courts, which can impose sentences ranging from three years in prison to death, have now been set up in the northwestern and central military administrative districts, the official <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rangoon </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday, quoting new orders dated Aug. 2. A transcript of the report was available Wednesday in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>. The new orders also extended the authority to dispense martial law to junior commanders in both areas. On Aug. 8, 1988, tens of thousands of people took to the streets of <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> to protest a quarter century of harsh socialist rule. The following day, troops shot and killed hundreds of unarmed protesters. Although <PERSON> Saw </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> has promised to hold multiparty elections next year, martial law forbids open political dissent. However, Western diplomats in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> reported a number of small protests by students who braved martial law to commemorate last year's protests. One diplomat reached by telephone from <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> on Wednesday quoted a witness who reported seeing a student clubbed on the head with a rifle butt Tuesday. Troops at the time were reportedly dispersing about 70 demonstrators and 200 bystanders in the center of <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>. Five people were arrested, said the diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity. The diplomat said there were also reports from the northern city of <LOCATION> Mandalay </LOCATION> that several thousand monks had mounted a protest Tuesday. He said groups of up to 300 monks walked in single file past heavy concentrations of troops brought into the city to ward off protests. The action was interpreted as `` a pointed protest showing the feeling of the monks against the regime,'' the diplomat said.
