<FIRST>r a AM-UnearthedCadavers     08-09 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Unearthed Cadavers,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buried Medical School Bodies Give Glimpse of Lost Profession</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As grave robbers go, <PERSON> Grandison </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> was pretty good. Purchased as a slave in 1852 by the <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> was a `` resurrection man,'' who dug up new graves in black cemeteries, cracked open the crude wooden coffins, bagged the contents and delivered them to the medical college for dissection by students. A century after a law change that made the craft obsolete, <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>' handiwork is coming to light as workers renovate the basement of the old medical college building. This week, about 40 boxes of bones from 19th century dissections were taken to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> to be studied at <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> for insights on the health, nutrition and lifestyles of Georgians in the 1800s. Campus officials are unsure how many bodies are in the boxes. Student volunteers also collected coins, buttons, bottles, surgical instruments, test tubes and clothing from the earthen basement of the 1835 building. `` I can think of no other archaeological find in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> remotely like it,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blakely </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> anthropologist. `` There may be other medical colleges that have things like this in their cellars, but they have n't been discovered.'' Records by <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Newton </PERSON>, dean of faculty at the college in the mid-1800s, indicate that grave-robbing was a booming business until 1887, when the laws changed. Grave-robbing was often the only way medical schools could get around laws that equated human dissection with desecration. <PERSON> Newton </PERSON> bought 2,000 gallons of whiskey in the 1850s and made references to transactions such as, `` Joe for subject, $ 10.'' The `` subjects'' were preserved in <LOCATION> Newton </LOCATION>'s whiskey until the time came for them to provide medical students vital lessons on the basics of human anatomy. The bodies were mostly blacks because `` when you have a large population of a depressed class, you're going to have fewer problems robbing their graves than the mayor of <LOCATION> Augusta </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moores </PERSON>, a hematologist and historian of the medical college. A manuscript on the resurrection man's career by the late <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, a professor of anatomy at the college, recounts how <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> performed his job, digging into graves by moonlight, smashing the crude wooden coffins with an ax, removing the `` subject'' and placing it in a sack, which he carried to the college in a horse-drawn cart. Sometimes, on his return, <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> would stop for a drink. One tale recounts how a student once removed the corpse while <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> was in the saloon and climbed in the sack. He moaned in a ghostly voice when <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> came back to the cart: `` <PERSON> Grandison </PERSON>, I'm cold Buy me a drink.'' Legend says <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> replied: `` Get your own drink.'' <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> continued to work for the college after the Civil War provided his freedom, at a salary of $ 10 to $ 15 a month. He retired as a janitor at the college in 1905 on a pension of $ 10 a month. <PERSON> Blakely </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> State researchers believe the bones `` will cover the entire period the medical college was in that building, from the 1830s to the early 1900s.'' <PERSON> Blakely </PERSON> said the remains eventually will be returned to the medical college, where they will be cremated next spring with the remains of current dissections and buried with them in an annual memorial service.
