an economics specialist who became head of the <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. Another woman, lawmaker <PERSON> Mayumi </PERSON> <PERSON> Moriyama </PERSON>, will head the <ORGANIZATION> Environment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Eiji </PERSON> <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employers </ORGANIZATION>' Associations, told <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> that two women in the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> would contribute significantly to the revitalization of the party Homemakers were particularly incensed at the 3 percent sales tax passed in April. Five Cabinet posts went to the largest party faction, controlled by <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>, and four each to the next three largest factions. <PERSON> Ryutaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Hashimoto </PERSON>, most recently the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>' secretary-general, was named finance minister, while <PERSON> Hikaru </PERSON> <PERSON> Matsunaga </PERSON>, a former prosecutor, was given the important post of international trade minister <PERSON> Taro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakayama </PERSON>, a former doctor, was named foreign minister, and former <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> Minister <PERSON> Tokuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamashita </PERSON> was named chief <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> secretary, the main government spokesman. <PERSON> Ichiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Ozawa </PERSON> was named the new party secretary-general, and <PERSON> Shunjiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Karasawa </PERSON> became the new chairman of the party's decision-making Executive Council Both have acknowledged receiving legal donations from Recruit. Opposition politicians reveled in the upper house rejection of <PERSON> Kaifu </P