<HEAD>Letter Carrier Has 31 Years of Experience</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Adkins </PERSON> has carried the mail for 31 years, and even his wife's illness could n't keep him away from a ceremony Wednesday for the centennial of the the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Letter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carriers </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Adkins </PERSON>, 56, and <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> letter carrier <PERSON> Terri </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Page </PERSON> delivered a 3-by-5-foot postcard to the ceremony outside the downtown post office. Stamps have been affixed at each of the 47 states where the postcard has been canceled, and it will be sent via Express Mail to the remaining states, ending up in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> on Aug. 30, the 100th anniversary of the founding of the postal workers' union in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Adkins </PERSON>' wife of 40 years, <PERSON> Audrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Faye </PERSON>, entered <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> on Wednesday for cancer treatment, but he said she insisted that he attend the ceremony. `` She did n't want me to miss it,'' <PERSON> Adkins </PERSON> said. `` I've been with her since she was 16.'' <PERSON> Adkins </PERSON>, whose route includes downtown <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, says one of the biggest changes since he began work has been the amount of mail. `` There's a lot more mail to be delivered _ I'd say at least triple,'' he said. `` There's heavier volume _ more magazines, more bulk business rate, which we have to have to stay alive. `` They told me 20 years ago it would be like this. That's why I never slowed down.'' The <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, native said he and seven of his eight brothers served in the armed forces and went to work for the federal government. `` I j