 A convicted killer said he was depressed when he won a reprieve from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s electric chair and `` can hardly wait'' for his execution. `` I do not have a death wish,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamblen </PERSON> said. `` I would say I do n't care about living as distinguished from I want to die.'' `` I can hardly wait to sit in Old Sparky -LRB- the electric chair -RRB-. I'm curious about it,'' <PERSON> Hamblen </PERSON>, 60, said in an interview Tuesday with The <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Union </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> State Prison. <PERSON> Hamblen </PERSON> was condemned for the 1984 shooting death of <PERSON> Laureen </PERSON> <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> during a robbery at her lingerie store. He was sentenced to death after firing his public defender and pleading guilty. He also admitted an earlier murder in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. `` I'm not the least bit concerned about electrocution. I think it's spiffy,'' <PERSON> Hamblen </PERSON> said. `` If you've got to go _ why not? It's better than AIDS, better than cancer of the colon, better than slipping into senility day by day. I can think of a lot more ways I'd rather not die,'' he said. <PERSON> Hamblen </PERSON> said he was `` let down'' when public defenders won an indefinite stay from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on July 18 just five hours before he was to be strapped into the electric chair. <PERSON> Hamblen </PERSON> denied he was legally insane or incompetent, as defense lawyers maintained. `` I might be wacko ... but within the legal definition, I'm completely confident I know what I'm doing,'' <PERSON> Hamblen </PERSON> said The inmate said he could commit suicide in his cell if he wanted to, but does n't want to. He said the problem with suicide is that people think the victim is unable to cope with life. `` I just do n't care to cope,'' he said. <PERSON> Hamblen </PERSON> served seven years in the Marines and saw combat duty in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> before he was dishonorably discharged in 1953. He was married and divorced and spent 20 years in prison on rape and burglary convictions before his release in 1978. <PERSON> Hamblen </PERSON> said he returned to crime in 1984 when he killed a woman he described as a `` beer-drinking buddy'' in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. He was fleeing the murder charge when he robbed Mrs. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>' store.
