<FIRST>u w AM-S&amp;Ls-Glance     08-09 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Glance,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-S&amp;Ls, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are some of the highlights of the savings and loan industry bailout legislation signed into law by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Wednesday:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>COST</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The bailout will cost an estimated $ 159 billion through 1999, including $ 60.5 billion to meet government obligations incurred in the rescue of 223 S & amp; Ls in 1988, $ 74.2 billion to close or merge more than 500 more S & amp; Ls and $ 24.4 billion for the government's share of interest on bonds sold to help pay for the bailout Over 30 years, costs including interest are estimated at $ 285 billion _ $ 157 billion of which will come from tax revenues.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CAPITAL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Within four months, <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L owners must have $ 1.50 in tangible capital for each $ 100 in loans. By 1995, the standard will be $ 3. The provision is aimed at discouraging risky investments by the thrift owners. In addition, many of the accounting loopholes that allowed <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L owners to avoid capital requirements have been closed.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>INSURANCE PREMIUMS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Both S & amp; Ls and commercial banks will pay more for the government deposit insurance that protects savers' accounts up to $ 100,000. Bank premiums will jump from 8 cents per $ 100 to 15 cents. S & amp; L premiums will rise from 20.8 cents to 23 cents.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FINANCIAL STANDARDS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The bill pushes S & amp; Ls back into home mortgage lending and out of risky investments such as speculative commercial real estate projects and junk bonds. Thrift institutions will be required to raise the level of housing and housing-related loans in their portfolios to 70 percent from the current 60 percent. S & amp; Ls now involved in risky ventures will have five years to phase out these investments.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BUREAUCRACY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The lead S & amp; L regulatory agency, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, will be dismantled. Its regulatory divisions will be transferred to a new <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> agency. The fund insuring S & amp; L deposits moves to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which already insures commercial banks.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REAL ESTATE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> will be created to sell more than $ 300 billion in real estate now owned by bankrupt <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls. The <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> will do the work, overseen by a board headed by the treasury secretary. The government will be required to give housing authorities and non-profit agencies first chance to buy housing from the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ANTI-FRAUD PROVISIONS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is getting $ 75 million a year for the next three years to uncover and prosecute fraud at S & amp; Ls and banks. It is directed to establish a fraud task force in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, which has the biggest concentraton of problem S & amp; Ls. Maximum fines for financial institution fraud will rise from $ 5,000 a day to $ 1 million, the maximum jail term from five years to 20 years.
</TEXT>
