<HEAD>Critics Charge VIP Riders Taking Money from Historical Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANASSAS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> and his family like riding government-owned horses at <ORGANIZATION> Manassas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Battlefield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION>, but such VIP privilege may harm the park's historical interpretive efforts, employees say <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> and his three children _ <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>, 15, <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON>, 12, and <PERSON> Corinne </PERSON>, 10 _ are regular visitors to the park, according to the vice president's office. The family is accompanied by <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> agents and local law enforcement officials. They ride the park's nine horses _ normally used for park security patrols and not available for public use. `` You have the vice president riding <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government horses at a park that is designed for historical preservation and in which the staff is trying to control recreational use,'' said former park historian <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hennessey </PERSON>, now with the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> State Division of Parks. `` You have money going into maintaining these government horses ... while anyone can see the woeful condition of the rest of the operation. What type of message does that send to the public?'' Park Supervisor <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Apschnikat </PERSON> said that while the park's horses are not for public use, the visits by <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> and his family are `` a different situation'' and the use of national park facilities by members of the executive branch is common. Other guest riders have included <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who has been riding twice, according to park spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>. <PERSON> D