ermany </LOCATION>, and he said no immediate efforts in that direction were visible. The West German appeal was issued after a special meeting of <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>'s Cabinet early Wednesday. Only five of the 19 federal ministers were present. Many senior <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> officials, including <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, take their vacations in August. Due to the lack of a quorum, the Cabinet meeting was limited to advisory action. Inter-German Affairs Minister <PERSON> Dorothee </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilms </PERSON> has been criticized by West German newspapers for failing to return to <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> to deal with the refugee problem. Her spokesman said Wednesday she was ending her vacation early and was heading back to the capital. East Germans began occupying the West German embassies nearly two weeks ago, apparently out of frustration over the outlook for emigrating through official channels. The East Germans, who numbered 131 at the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> mission when officials closed the premises, have said they will not leave until they are promised exit visas for <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Seiters </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> mission would be reopened only when the federal government could ensure normal operations. The mission has functioned in place of a West German Embassy since diplomatic relations were established between the two German states in 1974. <PERSON> Seiters </PERSON> said those at the closed <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> mission would be allowed to stay until they `` decide voluntarily to leave.'' Mission spokesman <PERSON> Eberhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Grashoff </PERSON> said that as of midday Wednesday, none had left.
