<HEAD>Liquor Salesmen Describe Kickbacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The second and third liquor salesmen to take the stand at <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>'s tax evasion and extortion trial testified Wednesday that they, too, were forced to pay kickbacks on sales to Helmsley-owned hotels. <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> of Capital Liquors and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Pursley </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> both said they had to pay back 2 percent of their gross sales to four hotels _ the <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lane </LOCATION>, the Palace, the New York <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moritz </LOCATION>. The salesmen testified that their commissions were generally 5 percent on gross sales. They testified the payments were arranged by Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>'s top aide, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Turco </PERSON>, and that the kickbacks were no longer required after <PERSON> Turco </PERSON> was fired in February 1986. The testimony was elicited by prosecutors to support the most serious charge Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> faces _ the allegation that she conspired with <PERSON> Turco </PERSON> to extort payoffs and goods from vendors doing business with Helmsley-owned companies. <PERSON> Turco </PERSON> is on trial with her. Last week, the first liquor salesman to testify, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> West </PERSON>, said he was forced to kick back the same percentage of his commission to keep his accounts at <LOCATION> Helmsley </LOCATION> hotels in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. He said he gave about $ 10,000 in payoffs in 1984. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> testified that in addition he had to take on the task of acting as central purchasing agent for liquor for the hotels. Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> decided to set up the arrangment after she was told certain employees within the company were taking kickbacks from liquor salesmen. <PERSON> Pursley </PERSON> said he took over the task after <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> left at the end of 1984. He testified that at a meeting in February 1985 with other liquor salesmen, <PERSON> Turco </PERSON> discussed where payments were going. `` He told us all that none of the money was going to him. It goes to Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Pursley </PERSON> said, adding that <PERSON> Turco </PERSON> said he put the money in a special slush fund for Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>. He quoted <PERSON> Turco </PERSON> as saying that Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> said that `` since we were so free with our money, she was going to take it.'' <PERSON> Pursley </PERSON> said he paid an average of $ 600 a month for one year beginning in February 1985. He delivered his cash payments in envelopes to <PERSON> Turco </PERSON>'s office, he said. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> testified that he kicked back about $ 9,000 over two years. He said that one of the <ORGANIZATION> Helmsleys </ORGANIZATION>' real estate companies would send him an invoice for consulting fees and that he would send a check for that amount. Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> also is charged with tax evasion for allegedly disguising about $ 4 million in personal expenses as business expenses. <PERSON> Turco </PERSON> and another former aide, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Licari </PERSON>, are charged with assisting in that scheme. All three are on trial on the tax charge. The conspiracy charge carries a maximum prison term of 20 years upon conviction. Penalties on the tax fraud charges range from three to five years.
