<HEAD>At the Movies: `The Abyss'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT Nolan to Bridges</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AP Arts: The Abyss</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 If E.T. took a little ocean vacation with <PERSON> Jules </PERSON> <PERSON> Verne </PERSON>, and dropped in for lunch with <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bridges </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Flipper </PERSON>, maybe someone would make a movie out of it. Maybe it could even be called `` The Abyss.'' The $ 43 million 20th Century <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> summer spectacular is about as derivative as any movie can get. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON>, who wrote and directed, pulls a litany of movie formulas and gimmicks, including a few from `` Aliens,'' which he also wrote and directed. What redeems `` The Abyss'' from being an `` E.T.'' or `` Aliens'' rip-off are some spectacular special effects and camera work. <PERSON> Deepcore </PERSON>, a submersible oil rig, is working not far from where a submarine, armed with nuclear warheads, has crashed in a fantastically deep trough. The government commandeers the mother vessel, orders <PERSON> Deepcore </PERSON> to take on a group of <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> SEALS and work with the divers to salvage the sub. At the same time, a hurricane rages above and an alien nation broods below. It seems the hurricane was a little something the aliens whipped up to protest nuclear weapons. The aliens, who move faster than a speeding bullet and who are definitely more powerful than any locomotive, also are responsible for the sub crash. Still, they are friendly, peace-loving little shards of light, vaguely reminiscent of the ethereal creatures in <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>'s `` Cocoon. <PERSON> Deepcore </PERSON>'s crew is a lovable bunch of hardcore riggers led by <PERSON> Bud </PERSON> <PERSON> Brigman </PERSON> -LRB- Ed <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> -RRB-. His estranged wife, <PERSON> Lindsey </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Mastrantonio </PERSON> -RRB-, designed the rig and brings down the SEALS for the salvage operation. The SEALS have a definite attitude problem, and their leader, Lt. <PERSON> Coffey </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Biehn </PERSON> -RRB-, is certifiable. The hurricane causes an above-water crane to crash down on <LOCATION> Deepcore </LOCATION>, and drags it the brink of the underwater trough. After communciation is severed with the mother ship, <PERSON> Coffey </PERSON> goes solo and decides to arm one of the sub's nuclear warheads, terminate the aliens and kill <PERSON> Deepcore </PERSON>'s crew. Before his ultimate demise, <PERSON> Coffey </PERSON> manages to arm one of <PERSON> Deepcore </PERSON>'s mini sea <ORGANIZATION> Rovers </ORGANIZATION>, called Little Geek, with a nuclear warhead, aimed straight into the trough at the alien nation. The first two-thirds of `` The Abyss'' amount to a fairly good adventure-thriller, with lots of sparkling, hip dialogue, good character development and nonstop action. The last third is a joke. <PERSON> Brigman </PERSON> decides to don a dive suit and go into the trough to follow Little Geek. He uses a special, experimental <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> liquid mix as his breathing aparatus. Why does he go? Because it's a dirty little job and `` somebody has to do it,'' he says with a straight face. This and other cliches pop up with astonishing frequency as `` The Abyss'' begins its plunge into movie camp. There are odd moments: <PERSON> Lindsey </PERSON> drowning in freezing water and then being revived by <PERSON> Bud </PERSON> slapping her face and calling her names after adrenalin and shocks have failed; a syrupy and trite <PERSON> Lindsey </PERSON> confessing to all sorts of mistreatment to <PERSON> Bud </PERSON> as he almost loses conciousness at depths no human has ever gone. There are pure ripoffs: an alien finger resembling little E.T.'s spindly appendage reaching out and touching a human _ much the same way as in `` E.T. The Extraterrestrial,'' and <PERSON> Michaelangelo </PERSON>'s ceiling in the Sistine Chapel But <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mastrantonio </PERSON> are a good blend, and the Deepcore crew is an interesting lot, thanks in part to <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Feuer </PERSON>'s casting Still, it's a formula group: a strong woman who helps leads the crew from disaster; a black; a burly, football type; a comic who travels with his pet mouse; a laidback guy named <PERSON> Jammer </PERSON> who comes through when the going gets real rough. <PERSON> Mikael </PERSON> <PERSON> Salomon </PERSON>'s photography is superb, and the original music by <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Silvestri </PERSON> has just the right taste of suspense and promise. But in the end, `` The Abyss'' promises so much and delivers so little. Produced by <PERSON> Gale </PERSON> <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON>, `` The Abyss'' is rated PG-13 for language and thrills.
