<SECOND>AM-Lesbian Soldier,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lesbian Soldier Can't Re-Enlist in Army, Appeals Court Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROCKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court has barred an <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> sergeant from re-enlisting because she is a lesbian, saying sexual orientation is important for maintaining discipline and the integrity of command. The 7th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> reversed a lower court decision allowing <PERSON> Miriam </PERSON> <PERSON> Ben-Shalom </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>, to rejoin the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>. The Army had refused to allow her to re-enlist because of her professed homosexuality. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Berigan </PERSON>, Ms. <PERSON> Ben-Shalom </PERSON>'s attorney, said she will appeal. `` It's our intent to keep up with the appeals and go as far as we can,'' he said from his home in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>. Tuesday's ruling reversed a January decision by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Myron </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> said Ms. <PERSON> Ben-Shalom </PERSON>'s First Amendment rights to freedom of speech were violated by an Army regulation barring homosexuals. Ruling on the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s appeal, the three-judge appeals court panel found that while Ms. <PERSON> Ben-Shalom </PERSON>'s declaration of homosexuality is speech, it is also an acknowledgement of identification in a group. `` It is the identity that makes her ineligible for military service, not the speaking of it aloud,'' Judge <PERSON> Harlington </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> wrote in the decision. `` Thus, if the Army's regulation affects speech, it does so only incidentally, in the course of pursuing other legitimate goals.'' The appellate court agreed with the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s argument that it needs to distinguish military personnel on the basis of sexual orientation to maintain discipline and preserve the integrity of rank and command. The court also found that Ms. <PERSON> Ben-Shalom </PERSON>'s 5th Amendment right to equal protection under the law had not been violated. Ms. <PERSON> Ben-Shalom </PERSON> was traveling in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and could not be reached for comment, said a friend, <PERSON> Hope </PERSON> <PERSON> Gentle </PERSON>, contacted at Ms. <PERSON> Ben-Shalom </PERSON>'s home in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyle </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> attorney who argued the case before the appellate court for the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, declined to comment. Ms. <PERSON> Ben-Shalom </PERSON>, 40, was discharged from the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> in 1976 after she said she was a lesbian. After a series of court actions, she was reinstated in September 1987. Ms. <PERSON> Ben-Shalom </PERSON> applied to re-enlist for a six-year <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> term last August. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> ordered the Army to consider her re-enlistment without regard to her homosexuality. The Army refused to let her rejoin, but after <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> found the service in contempt of court in January, Ms. <PERSON> Ben-Shalom </PERSON> was allowed to re-enlist. The action was, however, made conditional on the outcome of the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s appeal to the circuit court.
