<HEAD>ACT Asks Stronger Federal Regulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group that monitors children's television asked the government Wednesday to regulate paid telephone message services pitched to young viewers and said calls to such numbers can bring parents unexpectedly large telephone bills. Calling it a pocketbook issue rather than a free speech one, Action for Children's Television requested the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to restrict such 900-number services. Its petition asks the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> to require <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to issue refunds on demand to parents for unauthorized calls made by their children, make a blocking device available to parents and itemize telephone bills `` for child services.'' The group's targets are the numbers advertised on children's programs shown on independent stations during weekday afternoon hours, when many `` latchkey'' children are at home but their parents are at work The 900 numbers invite children to talk to popular personalities and cartoon characters, such as the Tooth Fairy, Mighty Mouse or She-Ra and He-man, and often offer products such as posters, signs or shirts as enticements to call, according to the ACT petition. Although children are told they will `` talk to'' a character, they hear a recorded message instead, the petition says. In fact, <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> says that any 900 service for which it consents to do the billing must be a recorded message. It must also say what the call will cost, tell children to ask for their parents' permission and allow no `` funny technology,'' such as the service that told children to hold the phone to the TV while it bleeped out tones A typical call to such a 900 number might cost $ 2.45 _ $ 2 for the first minute and 45 cents for each additional minute. <PERSON> Andrea </PERSON> <PERSON> West </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION>'s product marketing manager for 900 services, said the company does n't issue all 900 numbers although `` we have some sponsors that do provide programming with licensed characters.'' Licensed characters are those for whom the rights are owned by a company. West said customers can contest their bills although <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T has no blanket policy on granting refunds. She said regional phone company have the choice of offering itemized billing and in some instances do offer blocking devices. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> says it set its guidelines `` in concert with'' the regulatory guidelines of the Children's Advertising Review Unit of the Council of Better Business Bureaus. The ACT petition calls the <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T safeguards ineffective. ACT President <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Charren </PERSON> said that although <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T may not issue all the numbers, `` the ones they bill are the ones we are talking about.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Better </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> unit that oversees children's advertising says it does not `` encourage or endorse this form of advertising to children'' but is proposing guidelines <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorsch </PERSON>, president and founder of <ORGANIZATION> Teleline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Beveraly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, one of the leading providers of such services, said research shows that an average call lasts less than two minutes, that children have asked their parents' permission and that children who do n't understand that the costs mount with the time they are on the phone probably could n't make a call in the first place. He said his company has worked closely with ACT and the business bureau to put out responsible programming.
