<HEAD>Police Fire Tear Gas at Campus Protesters, Detain Journalists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police fired tear gas at hundreds of black protesters marching from a university campus in defiance of emergency regulations Wednesday. Fifteen journalists were detained. At least 1,500 black students and other activists held a lunchtime rally at the mixed-race <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cape </ORGANIZATION> as part of a national campaign of defiance against emergency restrictions and apartheid laws. The protests, which have been marked by almost daily student-police clashes in the <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> area, coincide with the campaign for Sept. 6 parliamentary elections. The <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> excludes representatives of the black majority of 28 million. After the rally, police detained 15 reporters, photographers and cameramen for foreign and local news organizations for about four hours. They were placed in police vehicles and held outside the campus while police fired rounds of tear gas at the between 500 and 600 people who marched off the university grounds after the rally. The journalists were later taken to a police station and warned that they were under investigation for allegedly violating the 3-year-old emergency regulations that restrict press coverage of unrest. Enforcement of the press restrictions has not been comprehensive. `` About 20 policemen were firing tear gas at random as the marchers with placards came about a quarter of the way across the road, then moved back,'' said a journalist who watched the events. `` The police were firing tear gas over the cars passing on the road, then they went onto the campus and fired tear gas all over.'' It was not known whether any students were arrested or injured in the clash. The Argus, a <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> newspaper, said in an editorial Wednesday that the defiance protests, which began a week ago with black patients seeking treatment at white hospitals, were gathering momentum. The paper said organizations and individuals restricted under the 1986 emergency were refusing to `` meekly acquiesce in their own repression.'' `` The government's response has been predictable,'' said The Argus. `` It has furiously denounced the organizations leading the defiance and ordered a tough police response _ no doubt sensing that such handling of the situation could boost its flagging fortunes in the general election campaign.'' The 924,000-member <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> African Trade Unions is a leader of the defiance campaign, despite a government decree that bans the organization from engaging in political activity. The congress issued a statement Wednesday mocking Law and Order Minister <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON>'s comment that he will investigate the labor federation's breaking of the emergency restrictions. `` What he will find is that the vast majority of right-thinking <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africans </LOCATION> have stopped observing the state of emergency long ago,'' the statement said. `` Not only are these regulations incomprehensible and unenforceable, but people do not regard themselves as bound by laws which they had no say in passing.''
