<HEAD>Executive, Summoned to Court, Enters Plea on Company's Behalf</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SE2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A chemical company's chief executive entered a guilty plea for his company Wednesday before a federal judge who demanded to see the `` top man'' before allowing it to plead guilty to polluting a waterway. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON> told <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuttle </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s chief executive and chairman, that he wanted to send a message that companies and the people who run them must be accountable when they damage the environment. When natural resources `` are gone, they are gone,'' <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON> said. `` I'm one of those judges who wants to get someone's attention, from someone who can do something about it. That's why you're here. <PERSON> Tuttle </PERSON>, who calmly and politely answered <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON>'s questions, apologized for the accident and said his company has spent millions of dollars to improve environmental protection and safety at its <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION> plant since the January 1985 spill. He said he was confident the accident would not be repeated. <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION>, a Philadelphia-based chemical company, is merging with the French petrochemical company <ORGANIZATION> Elf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aquitaine </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON> said while there was no way the court could monitor <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> Elf </ORGANIZATION>'s future performance, he believed <PERSON> Tuttle </PERSON> was sincere in promising the company would do better. `` I assure you it will,'' <PERSON> Tuttle </PERSON> replied. Environmentalists and legal experts have said that by requiring <PERSON> Tuttle </PERSON> to appear in person, <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON> could set a precedent for punishing corporate negligence. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, prosecutor in the case, said he thought <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON>'s actions would serve as a strong deterrent `` I'm sure Mr. <PERSON> Tuttle </PERSON> is not experienced in standing up before a federal judge,'' <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said. `` For him to have to come here and answer the judge's questions, I'm sure it got his attention.'' <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> was charged after a tank spilled at least 75,000 gallons of bleach into <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION>'s Hylebos Waterway, which empties into Puget Sound. The bleach, sodium dichromate, contained hexavalent chromium, which can cause cancer when inhaled in a dry form. In court Wednesday, <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said `` there was a negligent failure to test the tank for structural integrity.'' He said <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> has since moved its caustic chemical tanks away from the waterway and surrounded them with a dike. In May, <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> agreed to plead guilty to five misdemeanor counts after criminal charges against four company officials, including three executives, were dropped. <PERSON> Tuttle </PERSON> was not charged. The company also agreed to pay a $ 500,000 fine and to create a $ 600,000 trust fund to pay for environmental improvements in the <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION> area. The plea agreement covered two counts of negligently failing to maintain adequate storage tanks, two of discharging pollutants and one of failing to promptly report the spill to the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>. Twice, however, <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON> refused to accept guilty pleas from attorneys and lower ranking executives of <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION>, demanding instead that the `` top man'' appear before him. <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> has said the case is among the first in which the government based its prosecution on corporate negligence rather than deliberate wrongdoing. It may also be the first instance in which a corporate executive has been ordered to plead the guilt of the corporation, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Skover </PERSON>, professor of civil procedure and constitutional law at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Puget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sound </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. After the hearing, <PERSON> Tuttle </PERSON> declined to speculate on whether leaders of other companies might find themselves in a similar situation. `` The decision to come out here was not dictated by legal considerations,'' <PERSON> Tuttle </PERSON> said. `` We just thought that this was the best way to bring this situation in <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION> to a satisfactory conclusion. How other companies or other CEOs are going to react I really have no way of knowing.'' <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON> repeatedly asked <PERSON> Tuttle </PERSON> who would be accountable for the spill and for preventing a recurrence. `` I'm here to tell you that as chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> that I'm here to represent <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> and say that <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> is responsible,'' <PERSON> Tuttle </PERSON> said.
