<HEAD>Pony Owner Billed By Railroad For Service Disruption</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMAGANSETT, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cupcake, the pony whose errant hoof disrupted service on the <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rail </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION>, now has another tale of whoa. <ORGANIZATION> LIRR </ORGANIZATION> officials are demanding a $ 2,625 payment for the buses it was forced to hire to get commuters to their destinations when the pony's hoof was stuck between train tracks in December, setting off a two-hour delay. Railroad officials said in a letter this week to Cupcake's owner that if she did not pay the expenses within 30 days they would take her to court. The iron horse can wait until the cows come home, said owner <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Eggers </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Amagansett </LOCATION>. She's not paying. `` I think this is a very high and mighty way to handle what happened,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Eggers </PERSON> who owns two other ponies. `` This is outrageous.'' Cupcake, 19, escaped during the night from the barn in the Eggers' backyard. `` We had just built a new barn and apparently the latch was faulty,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Eggers </PERSON>. Cupcake trotted over to the railroad tracks, a few miles away, where his hoof got stuck. The Eggers were called early in the morning and told their horse was stalling train traffic. `` When we got there Cupcake looked so sad,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Eggers </PERSON>. `` His head was slumped down and he looked like he had just given up any chance of ever being free again.'' A veterinarian injected the horse with a sedative. Rescue workers then picked him up by his tail, lifting him uninjured from the railroad ties. `` What happened was not our fault, not Cupcake's fault,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Eggers </PERSON>. `` There is just no way we are going to pay for this.'' `` We think Cupcake is getting a bad rap,'' she said. <ORGANIZATION> LIRR </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> said he regrets what happened to Cupcake, but the owner should