<SECOND>AM-Arms Talks,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moscow Urges Accord On Nuclear Testing This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Soviet arms control negotiator on Wednesday called on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to agree to monitoring measures for underground nuclear weapons testing by the end of the year. <PERSON> Igor </PERSON> <PERSON> Palenykh </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s chief envoy to the superpower nuclear testing talks, said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is moving `` too slowly'' on the issue and urged <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to respond to a Soviet proposal. He called for the talks to be wrapped up this year. A six-week round of negotiations that ended Tuesday produced agreement on some `` important technical aspects'' for possible inclusion in a testing accord, <PERSON> Palenykh </PERSON> told a news conference. The talks are to set verification provisions and secure <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approval for two 1970s unratified superpower nuclear accords. But negotiations stalled over the monitoring techniques for atomic weapons tests, <PERSON> Palenykh </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiator <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> has said `` high-level decisions'' in the two capitals will be needed during the recess to move them along. No date was set for resuming the testing talks. The next phase of negotiations will focus on a nuclear test ban. <PERSON> Palenykh </PERSON> said he hoped Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Scecretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> would discuss the testing accord at their Sept. 19-20 meeting in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The Soviet proposal would allow use of both remote seismic or on-the-spot monitoring for `` any explosion starting from a certain threshold.'' He did not specify the threshold <PERSON> Palenykh </PERSON> said. `` We favor the idea of combining various methods of verification. Of course it will be the right of each side to use the methods in its own combination,'' he said. He said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> wants to use only an on-site method in which blasts are measured by a cable placed down a hole near the explosion site. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> says its method is the most accurate. The Soviets say remote monitoring of the shock waves is precise enough, simpler and less expensive. The talks are to establish verification provisions for the unratified 1974 Threshold Test Ban Treaty for nuclear weapons tests and the 1976 Peaceful Nuclear Explosions Treaty on non-military blasts. Both limit the power of explosions to 150 kilotons, the equivalent of 150,000 tons of TNT. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> rejected the original accords, arguing they could not be enforced. Most military analysts agree, however, that both sides have generally abided by the limits.
