Detectives went door-to-door Wednesday, but a police spokesman, Sgt. <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, said, `` They have n't narrowed it down to any specific suspects.'' `` She's trying to protect her neighborhood, her kids,'' said <PERSON> Marguerite </PERSON> <PERSON> Wise </PERSON>, who lives around the corner and knew the family because their children were good friends. `` That woman never hurt anybody.'' She said she was angered by the drug dealers that plague the neighborhood, but is afraid to complain to police. `` On my block I see what goes on but I shut up,'' she said. `` I'm afraid for my life and my kids.'' While women with baby carriages and children congregated in front of the <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON>'s apartment, a block away a half-dozen or more drug dealers impassively continued their trade, selling heroin under brand names like `` Terror'' and `` Steel Ball.'' A police cruiser stopped at the intersection and two officers bolted out, hands on their holsters, and headed toward a group of men huddled together. The men ran in all directions and the police nabbed only one, who had a pocketful of cash but no drugs, and so was let go. Less than an hour later, the heroin hawkers were back. `` It's wheeling, dealing over here,'' the man sitting on his stoop said. He declined to give his name, saying he was afraid the dealers would come after him, even though he lives in <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION> and was only visiting relatives. `` If I can notice it, what's their problem?'' he asked, referring to the police. The two officers assigned to guard the home said they realize what's going on around them, just out of sight, but said they do n't have the answers `` Drugs is a way of life around here,'' one said, speaking on condition that his name not be used. `` This is an every day thing.'' `` The drug problem's one thing, but the violence has gotten worse, even toward police officers,'' his partner said.
