 Moslem fundamentalists threw firebombs at Christian-owned shops in a provincial town to avenge an affair between a Moslem woman and a <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> man, police said Wednesday. A police officer said on condition of anonymity that `` many people'' were injured and 35 were arrested after an unspecified number of Moslem fundamentalists went on a rampage in northern Mahmoudeya late Monday. He said he expected 65 more would be detained. No weapons other than the firebombs were used, and police did not clash with the attackers, the officer said. The identities of neither the Moslem woman nor the Christian man were released. The daily state-run <ORGANIZATION> Al-Akhbar </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday Moslem extremists set fire to an appliances store in the Nile Delta town 85 miles north of <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>. The paper said many of the 35 arrested came from neighboring towns. The police officer said the incident occurred after a Moslem woman reported her affair with a Christian man to police. Friends decided to avenge the woman, who was unable to marry the Christian man. Egyptian law says a Moslem woman can only marry someone of her own faith, and the man was apparently unwilling to convert to Islam to marry her. Although the woman consented to the relationship, she was afraid of her family's reation, the officer said. She asked for protection, he said. In rural areas, there have been reports of fathers killing daughters who have had sexual liaisons before marriage. It was the second incident this year of an attack on Christians who engage in liaisons with Moslem women. The first occured May 1 in southern <LOCATION> Assiut </LOCATION> when seven Moslem fundamentalists broke into the home of a Christian student, killing him and wounding another <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> man and two Moslem women in the house.
