<HEAD>24,000 Gather in Remembrance of Atom Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAGASAKI, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 24,000 people on Wednesday mourned the victims of the world's largest atom bomb used against humans and called for <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to strengthen its ban on nuclear warheads. In <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION>'s Peace Park, the crowd commemorated the day 44 years ago when the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> dropped an atom bomb on this western coastal city. The world's first atomic attack had been carried out three days earlier in <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION>, killing 140,000 people. The bomb that hit <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION>, dubbed `` Fat Man,'' was more powerful. But because of the city's many hills, the damage was contained and 70,000 died, more than half the population. The city's call for stepped-up enforcement of a national policy banning nuclear warheads, including those on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ships at Japanese ports, may command the attention of the government now that the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> have been weakened by a series of scandals and unpopular policies. Under the 1951 U.S.-Japan Security Treaty, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> pledges to notify <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> if it plans to bring nuclear arms into the country. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> says the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has never consulted with it, and so it believes such weapons have not entered <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Critics charge the government uses the agreement to avoid the question of whether <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ships dock in the country with nuclear weapons aboard. `` It is a government's duty to its citizens to strive to shed light upon the truth, not to wait passively for prior explanations,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Hitoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Motoshima </PERSON>, an independent. <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> Chairwoman