<HEAD>Thousands Of Jews Pray At Western Wall To Mourn Lost Temple</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of Jews prayed Wednesday night at the sacred Western Wall in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to mourn the destruction of their temple by the Romans 1919 years ago. The nightlong prayer marked the start of <PERSON> Tisha </PERSON> <PERSON> Be-Av </PERSON>, or the ninth of the Jewish lunar month of Av, the greatest day of mourning in the Jewish calendar. The holiday this year was also marked by heavy security measures linked to the 20-month-old Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied territories and the annexed east <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> and fears of a possible terror attack. Hundreds of police officers and paramilitary border policemen guarded the Western Wall square inside the walled <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Police also erected a special electronic gate at the entrance to the Western Wall square and said no weapons would be allowed near the sacred stones. <PERSON> Tisha </PERSON> <PERSON> Be-Av </PERSON> commemorates the destruction of the First Temple in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> by the Babylonians in 586 B.C. and the destruction of the Second Temple by the Roman emperor <PERSON> Titus </PERSON> in 70 a.d. The Western Wall is the last remnant of that temple. The body of Jewish religious teachings lists other disasters said to have accurred on that day, such as the fall of <PERSON> Beitar </PERSON>, the last stronghold of anti-Roman Jewish rebels, in 135 A.D. and the creation of a Roman temple in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> a year later. During the ages, <PERSON> Tisha </PERSON> <PERSON> Be-Av </PERSON> had become a symbol of misfortune and persecution that befell the Jewish people. The expulsion of Jews from <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> in 1492, during the period of the Inquisition, is also said to have occurred on that day. The mourning for past tragedies is marked by fasting and prayer. Near the Western Wall, religious Jews chant sections from the Scroll of Lamentations or the Book of Job, sitting on the ground or on low stools. <PERSON> Tisha </PERSON> <PERSON> Be-Av </PERSON> lasts from nightfall till afternoon on the next day. During that period, Jews are forbidden to eat, drink, and bathe. Although work is technically allowed, it is customary to abstain from it. Many Israeli businesses closed for 24 hours. Restaurants and movie houses also closed or faced a fine.
