<HEAD>Antarctica Expedition Sleds Crash; Reduced to 2{ Sleds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Explorers crossing <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION> with dog sleds spent the past two days trying to salvage two of their three sleds, which were damaged when they crashed in a descent on ice, a spokeswoman said Wednesday night. The international team led by <PERSON> Minnesotan </PERSON> <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Steger </PERSON> tore down both damaged sleds and reconstructed them into one full-sized sled and a half-sized sled, said expedition spokeswoman <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> DeMoll </PERSON>. `` We were careening down some steep blue ice. The two Komatek homestead sleds crashed together and rolled, splitting the runners lengthwise,'' <PERSON> Steger </PERSON> said in a fax received Wednesday at the expedition's headquarters in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION>. `` It was a big mistake,'' he said. `` We should have been using ropes.'' Blue ice is hard, smooth ice that has been blown clear of snow. <PERSON> DeMoll </PERSON> said the accident occurred in an area with very low visibility, and the second sled could n't slow down on the incline. None of the six team members was injured, nor were any of the dogs. The team had been crossing its first piece of land, the <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> <PERSON> Peninsula </PERSON>, rather than the flatter, smoother ice shelf, and have encountered what <PERSON> Steger </PERSON> called `` a minefield of crevasses, many of them deep _ very deep.'' The 36 dogs, which normally run 12 to a sled, will likely be resdistributed along with the team's load as the group continues its 4,000-mile journey, <PERSON> DeMoll </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Steger </PERSON>'s group ruled out the expense of sending in a spare sled by plane, and instead hopes to make it until the scheduled resupply mission on Aug. 25. <PERSON> Steger </PERSON> and fellow International Trans-Antarctica Expedition members from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> since last month have been making a first-ever attempt to cross <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION> from west to east. The seven-month journey is designed, in part, to draw world attention to <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION>'s fragile environmental and political climate.
