<FIRST>r a AM-NorthropSuit     08-09 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northrop Suit,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawsuit Dismissed Against Aerospace Contractor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal government has dropped a lawsuit accusing <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> of falsifying tests on MX missile guidance devices and has agreed not to refile it, the aerospace company said Wednesday. Federal prosecutors could not immediately be reached to explain why they dropped the $ 3 million suit. It had alleged fraud and violations of the False Claims Act, saying tests on about 20 heat exchangers for the MX were never properly conducted. A lawyer for <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> `` whistleblowers'' characterized the suit as just a tiny piece of a mosaic of multimillion-dollar civil and criminal cases filed by former and present <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> employees and the government. `` Unfortunately for <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>, our cases are alive and well and moving through both the civil and criminal courts,'' attorney <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hafif </PERSON> said. The company has denied the accusations of overcharges and falsifying tests, which involve the cruise missile and stealth bomber as well as the MX missile. <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Cantafio </PERSON> said the heat exchanger suit, filed in federal court here in August 1987, was `` dismissed with prejudice'' by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON> last week, meaning it can not be refiled. `` The government's action in dismissing the case with prejudice clearly establishes that none of these violations occurred,'' a company statement said. Heat exchangers remove heat generated by a guidance system component known as the inertial measurement unit, a basketball-sized device that guides nuclear missiles to their targets. The case arose when a heat exchanger component and a test stand exploded during testing in January 1986. As part of the dismissal of the case, <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> agreed to pay the government $ 45,045 for the damage to government equipment. <PERSON> Cantafio </PERSON> declined to describe what led up to the dismissal of the suit, which the company announced late in the day. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> referred calls to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s special civil litigation section in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, which had closed for the day. <PERSON> Hafif </PERSON>, the lead attorney for several <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> employees who have sued <PERSON> Northop </PERSON> under the False Claims Act, characterized the case as relatively insignificant. `` <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> is a hell of a lot better at issuing press releases than it is at building missiles,'' <PERSON> Hafif </PERSON> said. `` That press release is designed to deceive the public and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> into believing that a small government case somehow affects our major cases and charges.'' The False Claims Act allows workers or executives who sue their employers for fraud against the government to recover as much as 30 percent of any damages awarded. The federal government has the option of joining such suits, but so far has not done so in an MX missile case <PERSON> Hafif </PERSON> filed on behalf of several plaintiffs led by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> employee. The case accuses <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> of overcharging, falsifying tests and using faulty parts on the guidance system for the MX missile, and <PERSON> Hafif </PERSON> said damages could run more than $ 100 million. The government has joined another of <PERSON> Hafif </PERSON>'s civil suits, a $ 30 million case involving allegations of faked tests on the guidance system for the cruise missile. A federal grand jury has issued a related criminal indictment accusing <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> and five employees of fraud and conspiracy for allegedly falsifying tests on nuclear-armed cruise missiles and for supplying equipment that the government knew failed to meet specifications. Another <PERSON> Hafif </PERSON> lawsuit involves allegations that <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> cost taxpayers hundreds of millions of dollars in overcharges and false tests on the stealth bomber. The government has so far declined to join that case.
