<HEAD>American Border Plants Ask Mexican Authorities To Help End Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American-run assembly plants are asking the government to help end a wildcat strike now in its third week that has idled 2,000 workers along the U.S.-Mexico border, company officials said Wednesday. `` Everything is on hold. We're waiting to see what the government will do,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaffney </PERSON>, vice president of the local industry assocation in <LOCATION> Reynosa </LOCATION>, just south of <LOCATION> McAllen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The strike involves a dispute between two labor leaders vying for control of workers in <LOCATION> Reynosa </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gaffney </PERSON> said. The strike is the worst to hit the border industries, which import raw materials and equipment duty-free, use cheap Mexican labor and then export the goods. It has idled 15 such plants since it began 16 days ago. Local industry has lost an estimated $ 500,000 daily said <PERSON> Osvaldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutierrez </PERSON>, another business leader. `` This is a very critical situation for <LOCATION> Reynosa </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Gutierrez </PERSON> said. `` Both local and international investors must have guarantees of labor stability if they're going to risk their capital.'' The so-called `` maquiladora'' industry is one of the fastest-growing maanufacturing activities in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. About 1,400 plants are strung along the Mexican side of the border, employing 392,000 workers. In 1985 about 800 plants with 218,000 employees were operating. <PERSON> Gaffney </PERSON> said the strike was caused by a dispute among <LOCATION> Reynosa </LOCATION>'s three unions representing the maquiladora industry All three are affiliated with the Federation of Mexican Workers, the country's biggest labor organization <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON>, general secretary of one union and a leader of another, is trying to control all three labo