<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0754EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-AnotherLook:NeedleSwap Adv14   08-09 1189</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Another Look: Needle Swap, Adv 14,1218</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Mon PMs, Aug. 14, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tacoma Needle Swap Program Studied, Copied Elsewhere</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Purchase </PERSON> spends most afternoons trading gossip with a slow parade of drug addicts on a gritty downtown sidewalk. But Purchase, a cheerful, engaging man, has something else to swap with the drug users he calls `` just folks'' and counts among his friends. `` How ya doin', pumpkin?'' he asks a woman with haunted eyes as he hands her a clean hypodermic needle for the used one she drops into a little red box sitting on a folding table. `` Not too bad,'' she says with a tired smile. `` That's great,'' Purchase booms. `` That's great.'' A woman with a headful of tiny black braids brings Purchase a pair of needles she had used to feed a heroin habit. She lingers in the feeble sunshine with fellow junkies to watch the action. Down the street, a squad car screeches to a stop and a policeman alights to drag a fallen-down drunk to the curb. `` I shoot heroin ... I'm a dope fiend,'' the woman with braids tells a visitor. `` But I come down here most every day for clean needles. I like the high, man, but I do n't want to die for it. I do n't want no AIDS.'' The 31-year-old woman, who gave her name only as <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON>, talks of enrolling in a treatment program to kick her 10-year habit. She points at Purchase. `` The rig man there _ he cares what happens to us.'' In this neighborhood of half-abandoned buildings, sagging fences, and weed-choked lots, Purchase and his crew of county health workers have built what is hailed as the nation's first successful program to reduce the number of dirty needles among drug addicts in an attempt to slow the spread of AIDS. The program, which swaps 1,500 clean needles for dirty ones a week, is being studied or at least partly duplicated in places like <LOCATION> Honululu </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. Observers are impressed by an unexpected bonus: new access to elusive inner-city addicts and a chance to help break their habits. Critics include <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration officials who say backers of such programs have yet to show they slow the spread of AIDS. State lawmakers and some treatment experts say <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION>'s program not only violates the state's drug paraphernelia law, but that it tacitly sanctions illegal drug use. `` To put up a little table to exchange needles like Mr. <PERSON> Purchase </PERSON> does is like Alcoholics Anonymous putting up a bar on the sidewalk and giving out free drinks while passing out pamphlets against drunk driving,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> Tacoma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> is just up the street from where Purchase hands out needles every afternoon but Sunday. Purchase has little patience for critics like <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>. `` You know what these people are really saying? They are saying, ` Let'em die.' Either that or they have n't seen the evidence that needle-sharing is spreading AIDS.'' Purchase, 49, a former drug counselor, won local government funding and staff in January after launching the program with his own money a year ago as a personal war on the spread of acquired immune deficiency syndrome. The $ 45,000 program's purpose is simple, he said. `` If you want to slow the spread of AIDS, you have to slow the spread through dirty needles.'' Homosexual contact has been surpassed by shared needles as a cause of AIDS' spread. Intravenous drug users account for 27 percent of all AIDS cases nationally; as of mid-July, 99,936 Americans had contracted the disease and 58,014 of those had died. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, 1,383 had been diagnosed and 753 of them have died. Purchase's war on dirty needles has drawn applause in the sad underground of street addicts and among many health officials. But he is quick to note he'd be out of business if authorities decided to enforce a misdemeanor state law against delivering or possessing syringes without a prescription. <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION> officials have permitted the program to continue because `` these people are not trying to commit criminal acts'' but rather are waging a war on AIDS, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Felnagle </PERSON>, chief criminal deputy prosecutor for <LOCATION> Pierce </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Purchase, a drug counselor for 20 years, says he owes addicts a great deal. which is why he contracted with a medical supply house a year ago to distribute needles himself, no questions asked. `` I worked in the business since 1969. These people paid my mortgage, put food on my table; I mean I've been living off their misery for 20 years like any decent social worker. I decided to do something for them.'' County Health Director Dr. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, is excited at the new bridge to this industrial port city's most elusive underclass _ longtime IV drug users. `` You do have to go to people you might not feel comfortable with, on their terms, and be willing to wash their feet, so to speak, if you want to reach them.'' Working out of a van, Purchase and his crew also hand out condoms, little bottles of bleach to clean needles, and blueberry muffins. An outreach health worker is always with them, ready to offer counseling and other help. County officials say they have found a `` substantial decrease'' in needle sharing as a result of the program and have referred more than 150 addicts for treatment after Purchase and his crew cultivated a relationship with them. Opponents like <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> and state lawmaker <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION> physician who failed this year to win legislation against needle exchange, note that backers have not demonstrated the program slows the spread of AIDS. Worse, <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> asserts, the program is unnecessary because AIDS among local IV drug users is no where near as bad as in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and elsewhere. `` They are using East Coast statistics to justify the idea here,'' he said. He bristled at the suggestion that he would just as soon let AIDS victims die. `` We spend over $ 2 million a year on drug and alcohol programs. Does that sound like somebody who wants to let them die?'' Another heath department spokesman, <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Reid </PERSON>, said it's unfair to expect the program to demonstrate in less than several years that it slows the spread of AIDS. `` How can you demonstrate success a year after the program starts when the incubation period for the disease is about seven years?'' Purchase puts it another way: `` If we're wrong, then we wasted a few cents a needle. If we're right, we saved a lot of lives.'' As a steady stream of addicts stopped at Purchase's table, <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON> leaned against a wall and explained addicts' willingness to use the program: `` We do n't have to give our name. We do n't have to do nothin' but bring the rig man a dirty needle for a clean one and the cops do n't bother us It's easy, and I think it's workin'. Hey, dope fiends are n't sharin' their needles like they used to,'cause they can get clean ones without a lot of problems.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for PMs Aug. 14</NOTE>
