<SECOND>PM-Religion in the News Adv 11,0804</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Fri PMs Aug. 11, or thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Many Hispanic Catholics Shifting To Evangelical Congregations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Although most were reared in Roman Catholicism, Hispanics in growing numbers are switching to evangelical churches, pleasing those congregations but worrying <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> leaders. Both seek to meet special needs of Spanish-descended Americans. Swelled by a modern tide of immigration, they now number nearly 20 million in this country, most of them Catholics. But studies indicate a heavy defection rate to Protestant churches of evangelical style. `` The movement of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Hispanics to evangelical Protestantism is a historic event of great significance,'' says the Rev. <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Figueroa </PERSON> <PERSON> Deck </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> specialist on Hispanic ministry. `` Protestantism is achieving a foothold in the Hispanic world, a massive presence, that it has never enjoyed before.'' Evidence of such evangelical inroads into Catholicism has turned up in many Latin American countries as well as in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Deck, of the <ORGANIZATION> Jesuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theology </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, says the success of the evangelicals `` is directly related to the heat, the passion, with which its adherents communicate their message.'' `` Hispanics generally like that,'' he writes in the national <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> weekly, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, but it's not the style of the typical orderly, reasoned <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Catholic service, generally shunning emotionalism. Surveys by the Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opinion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> indicate a steady increase during the last decade in the proportion of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Hispanics who are Protestants, now amounting to 23 percent. That is up from 16 percent in the l970's. In those years, 77 percent listed themselves as <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>, and 7 percent other or no religion, but the l982-86 figures indicate only 71 percent remain <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>. The Rev. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Greeley </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> sociologist, novelist and a senior associate at the research center, calculates Hispanic shifts from Catholicism to Protestantism at 60,000 a year _ nearly a million over the last 15 years. `` The Protestant segment of Americans of Hispanic origin is not only large, it is growing rapidly,'' he writes in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. He notes that the defection rate is lower among Mexican-Americans, 15 percent, than among Puerto Ricans, 24 percent, and others, 26 percent, and lower in the West than in the East. Storefront evangelical churches attracting Hispanics have proliferated in major cities in the East and also on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. `` More than three-fourths of the Spanish-origin Protestants are either Baptists or fundamentalists,'' <PERSON> Greeley </PERSON> says. `` Hispanics have joined fervent <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> groups in which their religion provides them with intense activity and community support,'' he says, adding that Catholicism apparently fails to meet those `` emotional, communal needs.'' The same point is emphasized by <PERSON> Deck </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> Hispanic Theologians in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He says the fundamental problem for Catholicism is the `` inflexibility of the parish,'' whose operations are `` often out of gear with the dispositions and needs of Hispanics.'' `` The sense of being at home _ achieving an environment that is welcoming and familiar _ is extremely hard to attain in the large, urban, ethnically mixed parish,'' he says. `` <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Catholicism is very uncomfortable with the cultural core of Hispanic Catholicsm: popular religiosity. It views all of that as at best quaint and at worst superstitious ... `` Enthusiastic religion and affective approaches are downplayed. ... Our liturgies are orderly and even elegant, our preaching calmly reasoned and conversational. Rhetoric and even eloquence are shunned. ...'' He says the evangelical <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> appeal to Hispanics stresses factors of `` personalism and community,'' small, hospitable congregations and ministers from the Hispanic community. To accomplish those characteristics, he suggests reviving the so-called national or ethnic parishes, popular in past periods of other <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> immigrants, now integrated into society, their special parishes outmoded. However, he says a new wave of immigrants indicates reviving such special arrangements to meet the need of Hispanics `` for a sense of acceptance,'' their `` own turf'' and ministers adapted to their language and customs. Such adaptations are applied in evangelical denominations such as Southern Baptists. It has 2,300 Hispanic pastors and a total of 2,612 Hispanic congregations, up 40 percent in this decade. Catholicism, although more than three times bigger, has fewer Hispanic priests _ estimated under 2,000. United Methodists are working to extend a National Plan for <ORGANIZATION> Hispanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, developed in 1986. <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> bishops at their June meeting in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, took steps for implementing a plan for special efforts among Hispanics to cope with evangelical proselytism. A Catholic bishop criticized some of that proselytism as deceptive. This was disputed by a <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> leader, who said Hispanics simply were being offered the Ggospel message of hope.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Aug. 11.</NOTE>
