<DOCNO> AP890809-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 1448EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv10   08-09 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 10,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release PMs Thursday, Aug. 10</HEAD>
<HEAD>Give Them Credit, But Not The Financial Kind</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumers have to be given some credit for the manner in which they have behaved in recent months, counting their money and retreating from high prices and borrowing costs. They beat the carmakers at their own game, declining to pay full price and forcing them to offer rebates and discounts in order to cut inventories. They have been slow to buy big-ticket appliances. They are cautious. They have slowed their acquisition of credit, in part because bank card borrowing comes at exorbitant rates these days and lenders refuse to come down in line with other rates. Consumer credit in June did rise, but the tendency to go into debt has receded over the past year. In May, the annual growth rate was 7.3 percent, but in June it dropped to 5.1 percent. The tendency of consumers to watch their dollars does seem contradicted by one area of credit: Bank card credit has continued to rise. However, the disinclination of banks to lower their rates _ 21.5 percent annual interest is n't uncommon _ that consumer resistance, so clear in other ways, seems almost certain. Buyers also slowed the rate of increase in home prices. By declining to chase the market, they've actually forced prices down in some areas, a rarity. Buyers now have the uupper hand in most of the country. They are showing their good sense in other ways too. Borrowing costs on homes are falling, and many homeowners are planning to refinance at lower rates. Again, it's a consumer's market: Banks are advertising for customers. Meanwhile, consumers have been strengthening their cash position. They have improved their savings; personal savings as a percentage of income in June rose to 5.9 percent from 5.4 percent in May and the total of $ 224.1 billion was the second highest ever. Personal income has been improving too. The improvement has n't been sharp but it has been healthy, especially since inflation has been relatively restrained Both, low inflation and rising income, reinforce higher savings. These and other factors, including an unusually strong employment situation, put the consumer in a strong position as the economy slows. In a sense, consumers are in a position to dictate in many areas of the economy. The situation is in stark contrast to conditions that prevailed in the 1970s, when the consumer was on the run. So desperate where buyers in that decade that they purchased in anticipation of price increases, and in so doing drove prices even higher. They were panicked, convinced that they could save by buying in advance of need. The situation today is reversed. Buyers are more inclined to sit and wait, convinced that waiting is the way to a better deal. They are patient rather than frantic. They are making the seller come to them. It is a rather rare situation, but it is one that might help to correct a slur on consumers _ that they are mere puppets manipulated by clever marketers. If they can hold their ground they might change some minds.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End advance for PMs Thursday, Aug. 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
