<HEAD>Fantasy Meets Reality</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Distant Voices, Still Lives'' opens Aug 13</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Terence </PERSON> <PERSON> Davies </PERSON> has been to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> a few times now, but the English director has n't stopped looking for <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> to appear whenever the clouds roll in. `` The first film I saw was ` Singing in the Rain,''' explained the 44-year-old director. `` What an introduction! I thought life was like that. When I'm in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, I still think that everybody goes to high school, everybody has a car, everybody's rich, everybody has wraparound teeth and everyone sings and dances so spontaneously.'' Hollywood musicals provided <PERSON> Davies </PERSON>, a native of <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, with the perfect escape from his own unhappy life. The youngest of 10 children, his father was a violent man who terrorized the family. He died when <PERSON> Terence </PERSON> was 7. Over the years, his older siblings filled in details of their father's behavior. <PERSON> Davies </PERSON> never forgot. `` When I was growing, I would get up and look at the house and go into the street and say, ` I must remember how it looks today.' I do n't know why, but I've got a very accurate visual and aural memory. I can remember conversations verbatim,'' he said. `` Distant Voices, Still Lives,'' his new film, represents just a fraction of those memories. <PERSON> Davies </PERSON> recreates his childhood by showing the pain of a working class family in <LOCATION> Liverpool </LOCATION> in the 1940s and'50s _ their hardship increased by a violent father. But like `` Singing in the Rain,'' or `` Meet Me in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>,'' another favorite of <PERSON> Davies </PERSON>, the characters of `` Distant Lives'' are sustained by music. At any time, someone is likely to break into song, maybe `` Bye-Bye Blackbird'' or `` Roll Out the Barrel.'' `` Pastoral Symphony'' and `` Hymn to the Virgin'' are heard in the film, too. `` The family would go to this pub and a few friends would be over and everyone would have a sing-song,'' <PERSON> Davies </PERSON> said. `` They'd go back to the house and have another sing-song Everyone did it. `` I remember my sister was going to buy ` 10 Cents a Dance' from ` Love Me or Leave Me' -LRB- starring <PERSON> Doris </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cagney </PERSON> -RRB-. I was agog for weeks on end. We were going to have <PERSON> Doris </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> singing in our house!'' <PERSON> Davies </PERSON> new film shows how popular entertainment mixes with real life and how the lines get blurred. He recalled the bright smiles and lilting melodies of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> musicals enhancing the dim environment of his own city. `` When you came out of the cinema into the slums, you did n't think, ` Oh how we're terribly deprived. It transformed the way you looked at your life. You thought, ` Is n't it fabulous? Was n't Doris Day fabulous in that number?' You were on a high for three or four weeks. `` My sisters went all the time. I was absolutely thrilled with ` Meet Me in St. <PERSON> Louis </PERSON>.' They lived on <LOCATION> Kensington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> and we lived on <LOCATION> Kensington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>. I was sure we were exactly alike. I was just sorry we did n't have <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Ames </PERSON> as a father.'' He first wanted to act, appearing in amateur productions of `` Uncle Vanya,'' `` The Cherry Orchard'' and many other plays. In 1972, he went to Coventry Drama and stumbled upon a chance to direct. `` I had written a screenplay, ` Children,' which was the first part of the autobiographical trilogy that I made over a period of 10 years. No one would do it. `` But there was a series on televison called ` Cinema Now,' and it told how I could apply to the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> for money. I sent a script in and a year later was asked to go to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> where I was told to direct.'' Life and fantasy again blurred. <PERSON> Davies </PERSON>, a complete novice at directing, was terrified on the set and remembered bitterly the crew's disrespectful treatment. Still, he fell in love with filmmaking. `` I realized when I looked down the camera the first time that this is what I wanted to do, even if I do it badly. You've captured a moment and there was magic between the filming of it and it actually taking place. It's still terribly exciting.'' By 1983, with the completion of `` <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON> and Child'' and `` Death and Transfiguration,'' the second and third parts of his trilogy, <PERSON> Davies </PERSON> had learned his craft. Each shot for `` Distant Voices'' was planned before the start of filming, and he quickly cast <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Postlethwaite </PERSON> and <PERSON> Freda </PERSON> <PERSON> Dowie </PERSON> as his parents. <PERSON> Davies </PERSON>' only concern was how his siblings would react to seeing their lives on screen. `` Their feelings were mixed,'' he said. `` It's opening up a lot of suffering, but they're also very proud I'm a film director and I go to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and have lunch at <LOCATION> Malibu </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> -RRB-. I thought it was a homage to them, I did n't feel it was dirty laundry. They suffered so much I thought it had to be told.'' Still, <PERSON> Davies </PERSON> is disappointed that directing has taken the magic out of his own movie-going experience. Reality has finally intruded on fantasy. `` As soon as you create something, you've lost your innocence. I miss going to the cinema and being absolutely transported by it. Now, I'm too critical.''
</TEXT>
