<HEAD>Philippines Land Reform Program Bogged Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Once hailed as the showpiece of President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s government, the land reform program is so bogged down in corruption and red tape and crippled by loopholes that even the official responsible for it wants to change it. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> signed the Comprehensive Agrarian Reform Law in June, 1988, to redistribute land to nearly 4 million peasants and free rural Filipinos from what she called `` their ancient poverty.'' Land reform was widely hailed as essential to defeat the 20-year-old communist insurgency in the countryside and break the grip on power enjoyed by powerful landlords. Last year, the government distributed 150,000 land titles covering some 254,000 acres. Most of the titles were awarded to rice and corn farmers, making the effort merely an extension of the land reform program decreed by ousted President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' program covered only corn and rice-producing lands but the Aquino plan encompasses all crop holdings. Critics claim the new law is so flawed that it stands little chance of achieving its goals and of being more successful than the dozen previous attempts at land reform since the 1930s. Under the program, expected to cost $ 10 billion, the government will pay landlords for their land. Those who then take possession must repay the government over 30 years at 6 percent annual interest. Militant farmer groups claim few can afford to repay and have proposed that peasants pay half a sack of rice per hectare -LRB- 2.47 acres -RRB- a year for three decades. Most critics also cite loopholes favoring landlords. Landowners can retain five hectares -LRB- 12.3 acres -RRB- plus three hectares -LRB- 7.4 acres -RRB- for each direct heir over age 15. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agrarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reform </ORGANIZATION> acknowledges that it is uncertain how much of the 24 million acres of agricultural land has effectively been removed from the program by exemptions. Under the program, estates of more than 50 hectares -LRB- 123.5 acres -RRB- are to remain untouched until 1992. The program also gives landowners the option of establishing profit-sharing plans for workers in lieu of transferring titles. Among those who opted for this alternative was Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s family, the Cojuangcos, who established a stock plan for workers on their 12,350-acre sugarcane estate in central <LOCATION> Luzon </LOCATION> A review committee suspended the implementation of the profit sharing scheme after critics claimed Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s family grossly undervalued their property. `` If land reform means to set the peasant free from the political and economic domination of the landlord which is the essence of a genuine agricultural reform program then, on the whole, it failed to break land monopoly,'' said <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Tadeo </PERSON>, leader of the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Philippines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peasant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>. `` What it gave were just crumbs, a few leftovers.'' In an attempt to get more large estates for redistribution before 1992, the government offered landlords the option of selling their property now. But in several cases, the government paid far more for the land than it was found to be worth, triggering allegations of corruption. The most controversial case involved the proposed purchase of 4,666 acres in <LOCATION> Camarines </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sur </LOCATION> province for the peso equivalent of $ 2.9 million. The sale was blocked when investigators found the land was worth only about $ 143,000. `` Those scandals have given more ammunition to those attacking the program,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Edsel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagman </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>' agrarian reform committee. `` Those supporting it are now wavering and the skeptical are slowly joining those who have been opposing it.'' The scandal led to the resignation of <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Juico </PERSON> as the agrarian reform secretary and suspension of a voluntary sales program pending a review of the more than 700 sale offers. <PERSON> Juico </PERSON> was replaced by Immigration Chairman <PERSON> Miriam </PERSON> <PERSON> Defensor </PERSON> <PERSON> Santiago </PERSON>, who recently told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> committee that the current law is `` a hodge-podge full of inconsistencies'' and should be amended. She said the provisions for establishing `` just compensation'' for landowners was too complicated and that the reform aspects of the program had been `` watered-down'' by landlord blocs in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Santiago </PERSON> also said the government lacks the money to purchase lands under the current system. The government had hoped to finance the program in part through the sale of assets recovered from <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and his associates. But so far, that effort has generated only $ 340 million. About $ 140 million in foreign aid is also available for land reform. Problems in the land reform program have given the rebel <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> a propaganda coup. It has announced its own `` land reform'' program in which it distributes to supporters property seized from landlords. The government estimates indicate the rebels have seized more than 76,500 acres nationwide, but rebel spokesmen claim to have handed out 111,000 acres in the central Visayas islands alone.
</TEXT>
