<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, Aug. 11, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet A.A. Termed ``Reconstruction of the Soul.'' ^With Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As head of the first Soviet office promulgating the tenets of Alcoholics Anonymous, <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuzmicheva </PERSON> says the approach makes for `` reconstruction of the soul.'' `` It offers not just recovery from alcoholism, but a program of spiritual recovery,'' she says. `` It brings out a completely new personality.'' Ms. <PERSON> Kuzmicheva </PERSON>, an attractive blonde Russian of 38 and coordinator of the newly opened <ORGANIZATION> Soviet-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alcoholism </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, says the A.A. technique is being found as effective there as in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. After all, `` we are human beings, all of us,'' she said in an interview. `` Due to the changes being made in our country, we also have been able to acquire the movement.'' Among participants, she said, believers `` speak of God'' helping them overcome their addiction. `` Others speak of a higher power. They all recognize they need a higher power exerted to help them. `` As to what kind, they need time to understand it is God.'' Such religious terminology may seem unusual for a health-promoting agency in an officially atheist society, but millions of people there are devout believers. However, <PERSON> A.A. </PERSON> itself steers clear of overtly religious affirmations or criteria, acknowledging only that help of a `` higher power'' is essential in overcoming alcoholism, but leaving that aspect undefined. Individuals may interpret that power as the group and its mutually supportive associations, or may consider it the Judeo-Christian God who acts in human affairs, or both. Whichever involves a spiritual dimension. It is purposely kept vague, so as to take in all comers. `` God as you understand him,'' Ms. <PERSON> Kuzmicheva </PERSON> puts it, using a typical AA phrase, meaning that the power is whatever recovering alcoholics consider it. `` They had lost control over themselves and lost the very quality of being human when they drank,'' she said. `` When they see life with sober eyes, miracles happen in their lives. They grow spiritually. `` They regain their best spiritual selves.'' Ms. <PERSON> Kuzmicheva </PERSON>, a professional educator who served as a factory personnel director before taking the post at the new <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> center, recently completed a month-long <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tour with three Soviet A.A. members. Accompanying them was the Rev. J.W. <PERSON> Canty </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Episcopal </LOCATION> priest who had established the new Soviet center, and who in 1987 had started the Soviet's first <LOCATION> A.A. </LOCATION> group called <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Beginners. He says Soviet authorities initially were dubious of the project, but their attitude has changed to `` cautious respect'' now that they are `` seeing alcoholics get a second chance at life.'' On the 16-city tour concluded in late June, the group had addressed school and church gatherings, met with numerous <LOCATION> A.A. </LOCATION> groups, usually in churches, but also with an atheist-agnostic <ORGANIZATION> A.A. </ORGANIZATION> group in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. They also toured various health facilities and met with former Presidents <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and their wives, attending a Sunday school class taught by <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> in his hometown of <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Kuzmicheva </PERSON> said the Scripture lesson, as <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> interpreted it, emphasized that when <PERSON> God </PERSON> gives his promises, they sooner or later are fulfilled `` This is very promising for our country,'' she said, adding that recent liberalizing developments there pointed toward a more fulfilling future. However, like <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the Soviet has immense problems with alcoholism. Soviet leader <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in 1985 launched a campaign against it, but popular resistance forced him to ease some of the restrictions. `` Unfortunately the problem is very acute in our country,'' Ms. <PERSON> Kuzmicheva </PERSON> said, estimating there are 10 to 15 million alcoholics in a population of 290 million. `` We have seen how strong and spiritual the A.A. movement is in this country and we hope to have the same success in our country,'' she said. `` It will work. It will work all over the world.'' On the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tour, the Soviet A.A. members often gave their testimony in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> meetings, using only first names as customary in A.A. Two of them were atheists, one of them a believer. They told of families breaking up, being repeatedly hospitalized, but not being able to quit drinking until admitting they could n't without help of a higher power. <PERSON> Saha </PERSON>, 43, an engineer and a non-believer puts it this way: `` With alcoholism, you have to admit despair before you experience victory.'' Ms. <PERSON> Kuzmicheva </PERSON>, not an alcoholic herself, says she is a believer, but not a regular church-goer. `` Many did not believe in God when they drank, but when they become sober, they begin to believe.
</TEXT>
