<FIRST>a a BC-BehindtheWheel Adv19-20   08-09 0843</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Behind the Wheel, Adv 19-20,0865</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug. 19-20, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ford Ranger Changes from Work to Play</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A funny thing happened to the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ranger </ORGANIZATION> on its way to becoming <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s compact pickup truck leader. It went from being a work truck to being a personal vehicle. The change was more than just semantics. It went below the sheet metal. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> increased the Ranger's horsepower, jazzed up the outside with two-tone paint and made the interior more car-like as the Ranger evolved over the decade and its sales rose to more than 300,000 a year. Today's 1989 Ford Ranger reaps the benefits of all the changes, with the automaker projecting at the close of the 1989 model year that the <ORGANIZATION> Ranger </ORGANIZATION> will retain its title as the top-selling compact pickup. The test vehicle was a 1989 Ranger XLT two-wheel-drive, the most popular Ranger model because it offers a number of optional features in one low-priced package. The XLT had such amenities as power steering, deluxe two-tone paint, a rear window that slides open and AM @ FM stereo cassette player with clock. Price out the door was $ 10,464. The test truck felt sturdy _ like a truck _ and easily maneuverable _ like a car. Its high profile offered a good view of traffic ahead, and its cloth bench seats with center armrest and easy-to-read instrument panel made for a comfortable interior. I did feel the jostling, shuddering of a truck-like suspension over big bumps but it was n't overly bothersome. There also was truck-like road noise. The all-terrain tires and rear antilock brakes gave surefooted confidence. The five-speed manual transmission was a bit notchy in its feel but it and the new-for -'89 four-cylinder engine with eight spark plugs performed <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> boosted the horsepower 10 percent this model year to 100 with the 2.3-iter, Twin Plug engine design that uses two spark plugs per cylinder. It helped give the Ranger a more peppy ride and more power for trailer towing. Fuel economy was commendable, with the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> rating at 23 mpg in the city and 27 mpg on the highway. I would n't advise trying to seat three across in the Ranger XLT regular cab. The middle person would either have the gear shifter between the legs or would have to sit sideways with the legs dangling over to the other passenger's area. This year <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> added a column-mounted automatic transmission shift lever to help solve this problem. If you get the manual transmission and carry only two people in the regular cab as I did, the legroom seems decent and seating is adequate. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> also offers a Super Cab that has the largest rear seating package in the compact pickup truck segment. Length of the test Ranger pickup box was 76.3 inches, bringing total vehicle length to 175.6 inches. While that's considerably shorter than the more than 194 inches of overall length of the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> F-150 full-size pickups, it's still sufficient room for hauling wood, furniture and the lawn mower, if the occasion arises. Men between 30 and 35 years of age are 85 percent of the Ranger buyers and they use the little pickup mostly for personal use, such as driving to work, according to <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Stajich </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> Division compact truck marketing plans manager. Sixty-five percent are married, but most do not have children. Many Ranger buyers are first-time truck buyers, he said, adding that two-thirds either trade in cars as they buy the Ranger or had a car as an alternative purchase. He called them middle of the roaders who are educated with somewhat upscale, contemporary lifestyles but are more entry-level in their purchases. `` They're looking for a good deal, a low purchase price,'' <PERSON> Stajich </PERSON> said. `` ... And they can customize -LRB- the Ranger -RRB-. It has high flexibility.'' He noted that when the Ranger first came out in 1981 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> saw the truck as something that would offer value to more traditional truck buyers _ older, married men who would want to get better fuel economy from their trucks. `` That was true for the first year,'' <PERSON> Stajich </PERSON> said. `` Then Toyota led the way, adding youthful appeal to their trucks ... In 1987, we revamped our marketing and made the Ranger sportier.'' Base price of $ 9,001 for the test Ranger is not the lowest among compact pickup trucks. A similar Chevrolet S10, for example, starts below $ 9,000. But <PERSON> Stajich </PERSON> said many of the features offered in the XLT package are separate options on other small pickups, such as those offered by <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION>, and thus could add up to a more expensive final price. Consumer Reports magazine rates the Ford Ranger two-wheel-drive with four-ylinder engine as average in its reports of trouble from owners of 1983-87 models.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Job </PERSON>, former executive business editor of The <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. She has covered the automobile industry for seven years.
</TEXT>
