<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When cable TV pioneer and movie buff <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> bought the MGM movie library three years ago, he got `` The Wizard of Oz'' _ but he ca n't show it on his own stations until 1999. Under an agreement hammered out at the time of the <ORGANIZATION> MGM </ORGANIZATION> purchase, the <ORGANIZATION> Turner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> gave up television rights to `` The Wizard of Oz,'' but obtained the rights to another classic, `` Gone With the Wind,'' <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>'s favorite film. <PERSON> Scarlett </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Hara </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rhett </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> thus left <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> for <ORGANIZATION> TBS </ORGANIZATION>, while <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Toto </PERSON> set up camp with <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>, which first showed `` The Wizard of Oz'' to television viewers on the night of Nov. 3, 1956. `` What happened was, <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> traded,'' said <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicol </PERSON> of TBS. `` We had the TV rights to ` The Wizard of Oz,'' but <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> really wanted ` Gone With the Wind.''' Even though <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> ca n't show ` Oz' on its TBS SuperStation or on <ORGANIZATION> TNT </ORGANIZATION> _ <ORGANIZATION> Turner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>, its feature entertainment channel _ that has n't stopped <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> and his companies from marking the film's 50th anniversary. Under license from <ORGANIZATION> TBS </ORGANIZATION>, MGM-UA Home Video will release its `` Golden 50th Anniversary Collector's Edition'' videocassette of `` Oz,'' complete with a `` commemorative videotape package.'' Fancy packaging aside, the new version is being touted as a videophile's delight _ fully restored, and with two added sequences: a dance reprise of `` If I Only Had a Brain,'' performed by <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolger </PERSON> as the Scarecrow, and another musical number, `` The Jitterbug.'' Both were cut from the film during editing. Missing from the home video version are the familiar black-and-white <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> sequences, before <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> crashes into Oz; that's because they are n't really supposed to be black and white. The film's first moments were originally filmed in sepia and white, for a softer transition to the Technicolor splendor of Oz. Later prints opted for the simpler black-and-white technique. `` It's a beautifully restored print, with the original Technicolor at its best,'' said TBS' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. `` And with the <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> sequences, in the original sepia tone ... it's really beautiful.'' It's not as if the old videocassette did badly; released in 1980, it's sold 600,000 copies in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to <ORGANIZATION> TBS </ORGANIZATION>. In addition to the new videocassette, <ORGANIZATION> TBS </ORGANIZATION> also is releasing the restored film for special screenings in theaters across the country, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. A new release of the score is coming out on compact disc, including a recording <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ebsen </PERSON> made during his nine days as the <PERSON> Tin </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodman </PERSON>. According to `` Oz'' film chronicler <PERSON> Aljean </PERSON> <PERSON> Harmetz </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ebsen </PERSON> suffered a debilitating allergic reaction to the aluminum dust the costumers dumped all over him and was hospitalized, leading to his replacement with <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Haley </PERSON>. And if seeing the movie and hearing the score are n't enough, `` Oz'' fans, under a `` worldwide licensing program'' of Turner Home Entertainment, can buy an oz-tentatious array of stuff: There's Oz clothing for the whole family, including maternity wear. Ties. Jewelry. Costumes of the Scarecrow, the Cowardly Lion and other characters. Greeting cards. Postcards. Buttons. Key chains. Calendars. `` Bendable toys.'' Giftwrap. Lunch boxes. Beach towels. All are for sale in `` The Turner Store,'' a souvenir stand in the lobby of <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>'s CNN Center building in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. Also available: `` dental reminder cards,'' to send cowardly patients off to see the dentist _ which for some, can be as big an adventure as going off to see the Wizard.
