<HEAD>`Bordertown' Filmed in Authentic Replica of Western Town</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Actor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Comar </PERSON> says the set built for `` Bordertown'' is so authentic a cowboy from the Old West could ride in and feel at home. An entire town was built on a ranch east of <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, for the half-hour weekly Western series on the Family Channel. Sixty-five carpenters worked 5 -LCB- weeks to build the half-million dollar town. `` Every building is complete inside and out,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Comar </ORGANIZATION>, who stars as <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Marshal <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Craddock </PERSON>. `` We film everything there, with no studio work at all. In the winter the streets are muddy. The prop people came in and _ in the general store, for instance _ they stocked every shelf and drawer. If you open the lace drawer there's lace in it. The saloon has antique bottles. The livery stable has period tack, and the saddles are a hundred years old.'' The show is set in a town that straddles the U.S.-Canadian border. <ORGANIZATION> Comar </ORGANIZATION> plays a gunfighter-turned-marshal, while <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> is <PERSON> Clive </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, a Canadian Mountie who goes strictly by the book. French actress <PERSON> Sophie </PERSON> <PERSON> Barjac </PERSON> also co-stars as the town doctor. It is a joint Canadian-French production that will also be shown in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Comar </ORGANIZATION> said he compares <PERSON> Craddock </PERSON> to a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> street cop and <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> to a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> bobby. <PERSON> Craddock </PERSON> is a functioning illiterate who is a pack rat and is terribly disorganized. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> is very organized and a member of a semi-military organization. They have a bit of an `` Odd Couple'' relationship. `` The authentic town and props help us get the feeling of what the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> was like,'' <ORGANIZATION> Comar </ORGANIZATION> said on a visit here. He was attired in his costume: chaps, a handmade gun belt, and a heavy-duty cotton shirt with a bib front that can be taken off when it gets dirty. `` <PERSON> Craddock </PERSON>'s looking for a soft place to retire. He's a former <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Ranger. He worked on a ranch near <LOCATION> Laredo </LOCATION> and killed a Mexican rancher's son while stealing horses in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. In retaliation they killed his son and daughter. That's when he went to <LOCATION> Bordertown </LOCATION> to ease the pain.'' The Western series has made a small comeback on the networks, which have two shows this year, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>' `` Paradise'' and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` The Young Riders.'' But the Western is thriving on the Family Channel. In addition to `` Bordertown,'' the cable network as `` Gunsmoke,'' `` Wagon Train,'' `` Bonanza: The Lost Episodes,'' `` The Big Valley'' and `` The Rifleman.'' On Saturdays and Sundays, the Westerns start at 11:30 a.m. EDT with `` <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>.'' The Family Channel has also ordered a new version of `` Zorro,'' to be made in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. `` They're considering a two-hour ` Bordertown' movie,'' <ORGANIZATION> Comar </ORGANIZATION> said. `` It would be the pilot we never made. It would be great to get a superior story and to be able to flesh it out. `` We sometimes have a guest villain on the show, but we try to concentrate on human relations. The things that are happening in the town. People get tired of violence, so the jeopardy caused by the bad guys is secondary. We've also had stories about real people. In one show <PERSON> Bat </PERSON> <PERSON> Masterson </PERSON> came to town trailing four men. In another, President <PERSON> Garfield </PERSON>'s life is threatened when he comes to town. He's assassinated elsewhere, however.'' <ORGANIZATION> Comar </ORGANIZATION> is a former stage manager and lighting director for rock groups and ballet companies. He lived in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> for two years and worked there off and on for six to eight years. During time off from `` Bordertown'' he went to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> to co-star with <PERSON> Susanna </PERSON> <PERSON> York </PERSON> in an episode of `` The Ray Bradbury Theater.'' Last summer, he played a television executive in the Home Box Office miniseries `` Glory, Glory.'' He was an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent in the <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> miniseries `` Echoes in The Darkness,'' and had roles is the movies `` Switching Channels,'' `` Short Circuit II'' and `` Big Town.'' `` My wife, <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON>, and I moved to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> a year ago but we've only spent three months in our house,'' he said. `` I've been working in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>. We're expecting our first child on Labor Day.'' <ORGANIZATION> Comar </ORGANIZATION> said when he auditioned for `` Bordertown'' it was for the role of the mountie. `` I'm well-educated, I'm neat, I hate guns,'' he said. `` I'm the complete opposite of <PERSON> Craddock </PERSON>. My wife hates it that I do n't shave for five months. She does n't mind the long hair.''
