<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mergers and acquisitions in the field of computer software and services slowed sharply in the first half of 1989, an investment banking firm said. The number of deals fell 12 percent and the value of the deals dropped 65 percent, reflecting the scarcity of mega-deals, according to <ORGANIZATION> Broadview </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> `` The industry is catching its breath after the exceptional levels of activity in early 1988,'' <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Federman </PERSON>, a partner in the firm, said in a news release Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> Broadview </ORGANIZATION> prepares the figures for Adapso, the <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, Va.-based computer software and services industry association. The biggest deal of the half-year was the $ 320 million purchase of <ORGANIZATION> Cullinet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Software </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the world's biggest software company. The figures did not include the buying spree of <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> because <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> did not buy entire companies. So far this year it has made 10 minority investments, <ORGANIZATION> Broadview </ORGANIZATION> said. The number of deals fell to 168 from 190 a year earlier, while the value of deals plunged to $ 1.9 billion from $ 5.4 billion. The value of deals was $ 2.1 billion in first-half 1987 and $ 1.9 billion in first-half 1986.
