<HEAD>Frederick Wang, Son of Wang Labs Founder, Resigns As President</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhotos NY80, LOW1 of Aug. 8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Industry analysts and Wall Street welcomed the decision by <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> to resign as president of the troubled computer company founded by his father. Share prices in <ORGANIZATION> Wang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> jumped 20 percent after the announcement Tuesday. Analysts said <PERSON> Wang </PERSON>'s resignation signaled the Lowell-based company's intention to get serious about its problems, which include a recently announced $ 375 million quarterly loss. `` Like a general who lost a battle, he accepted responsibility and it will have a beneficial effect on Wall Street,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Geran </PERSON>, a computer analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION> The stock rose to $ 6.87 -LCB- a share from $ 5.75 on the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Still, some analysts said the company will have trouble finding a strong, independent manager to lead it out of its troubles as long as <PERSON> An </PERSON> <PERSON> Wang </PERSON>, the company's 69-year-old founder and chairman, continues to exert control. `` A good aggressive executive does n't want to be No. 2,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. The 11-member board of directors assembled for a special meeting Monday night at <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> headquarters and the younger <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> resigned as president and chief operating officer. The board named as acting president <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> H.S </PERSON>. <PERSON> Chou </PERSON>, currently a vice chairman and director of the international computer maker. A search committee for a new president was formed. <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Wang </PERSON>, 38, is a computer mathematician who worked in the family business for 17 years. He was elevated to the presidency in 1986. `` There is a general perception that -LRB- <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> -RRB- was in over his head. But he was dealing with basic change in the minicomputer business,'' <PERSON> Geran </PERSON> said. `` I believe this action is in the best interest of <ORGANIZATION> Wang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> at this time,'' <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> said in a statement. `` Employees and customers will be best served by a speedy resolution to the company's current situation.'' <PERSON> An </PERSON> <PERSON> Wang </PERSON>, in a statement, called his son's resignation `` in keeping with his constant devotion to doing what he felt was in the best interest of the company.'' In November 1986, the elder <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> stepped down as president and was replaced by his son but retained the job of chief executive officer. The day his son resigned, <PERSON> An </PERSON> <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> had returned to work part-time after recovering from surgery for cancer of the esophagus. The younger <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> will remain on the board and undertake special projects. Prospects for the company `` depend on the health of the doctor,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said, referring to the elder <PERSON> Wang </PERSON>, who holds a doctorate from <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> in computer science and often is called by that title. `` If the doctor's healthy, they'll bring in a president and they'll try to resurrect themselves.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Wangs </ORGANIZATION> hold a controlling interest in the company and have resisted any suggestion they sell it, preferring instead to try to get the business back on its feet. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> analyst, said stockholders would benefit most if the company were sold or, at the very least, if <PERSON> An </PERSON> <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> stepped out of the way. Last week, the company announced a $ 375 million quarterly loss and said it it suspended dividend payments. Its financial predicament put it in violation of a bank-lending agreement, the company noted. Most of the quarterly loss resulted from a $ 237 million pre-tax charge to cover the cost of a restructuring that involved closing factories, cutting jobs in its worldwide work force of 28,000 people, and lowering the book value of outdated assets. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> stock has lost more than 80 percent of its value since early 1984, when it traded at more than $ 35 a share. Founded in 1951, the company made its reputation in the 1970s in office word processors. But sales began to slip with the increasing popularity of personal computers. Its minicomputer business fell behind as well, eclipsed by workstations. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Henning </PERSON>, a Wang spokesman, said Tuesday of the resignation, `` We wanted to give a consistent message that we are doing everything and anything possible, even taking steps that are painful,'' he said. `` We have a lot of work to do,'' he said.
