<HEAD>Government Reports Consumer Debt Rose at Slower Pace in June</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans took out $ 2.99 billion more in consumer debt than they retired in June, the government reported, as the pace of borrowing slowed in part because of declining auto sales. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that consumer credit in June rose at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 5.1 percent, down from May's revised 7.3 percent rate. The May increase was revised from $ 3.6 billion to $ 4.2 billion. Consumer credit increased 4.3 percent in April after rising 6.6 percent in March and 9.5 percent in February. Consumer credit increased 8.5 percent over all of 1988. Consumer spending is watched closely as a barometer of the economy's health since it represents two-thirds of overall economic activity. Economic growth has been slowing recently, prompting concern that <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> efforts to contain inflation could move the economy into a recession instead of the `` soft-landing'' it seeks. Economist <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaber </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a consulting firm here, said the fact that consumer spending does not appear to be collapsing helps take the heat of the economy and reduce inflationary pressures. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported earlier that retail sales had fallen 0.4 percent in June, dragged down in part by poor sales of autos. But excluding the automotive category, overall retail sales actually rose 0.1 percent, it said. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday that auto loans fell $ 267 million in June, a 1.1 percent decline on a seasonally adjusted annual basis. They had risen 4.5 percent in May and 3.3 percent in April. But Ms. <PERSON> Shaber </PERSON> said car sales increased in July, `` so I think that the business of liquidating car loans is a very temporary kind of phenomena that's not going to continue and you might see a little bit of increase in car loans in July.'' Leading the overall consumer credit increase in June was the category of debt that includes credit cards. It rose $ 3.1 billion, a 20 percent annual rate of growth, after increasing 13 percent in May and 11 percent in April. Ms. <PERSON> Shaber </PERSON> said this reflects a shift toward retail credit, `` to soft goods like apparel and small items.'' Bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate increased $ 404 million, a 2.5 percent annual rate of advance, but down from 7.2 percent in May and 2.8 percent in April. Borrowing for mobile homes fell for the fifth consecutive month, declining by $ 257 million or 12.9 percent on an annual basis. That followed drops of 2. l percent in May and 8.7 percent in The various changes left total consumer debt in June at a seasonally adjusted $ 701.19 billion.
</TEXT>
