ng from $ 14.75 to $ 18 between July 25 and last Thursday for a total of $ 10.3 million. <PERSON> Hinson </PERSON> said Thursday that Midway had not been approached by anyone seeking to take over the airline, despite heavy trading in the company's stock. Midway `` has no interest in being acquired,'' he said, attributing the stock activity to new interest in airlines as takeover targets. Midway was founded 10 years ago at the start of airline deregulation, when it served three <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> cities from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> _ <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>. The airline now serves 51 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cities, from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, and from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, she said. Midway recently announced it had ordered 74 new jets from <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell-Douglas </ORGANIZATION> worth about $ 2 billion. The airline, the nation's 16th-largest carrier, operates from <LOCATION> Midway </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Side </ORGANIZATION> and has 4,300 employees, Ms. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Ampco-Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> and its subsidiaries _ which include <ORGANIZATION> Buffalo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> _ make and sell engineered products. <ORGANIZATION> Ampco </ORGANIZATION> is the sole shareholder in the subsidiary holding the airline stock. The company is a mystery to some airline analysts. `` They are n't a big player,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Joedicke </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` I've never heard of them.'' <PERSON> Joedicke </PERSON> described Midway as a `` niche'' carrier, handling just 0.8 percent of the nation's air traffic. `` Their niche is that they dominate Midway Airport in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, which is much closer to downtown than <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` It has the advantage that a lot of businessmen appreciate coming into Midway from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Joedicke </PERSON> said. He said the carrier has `` developed quite a successful hub in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> for east-west traffic.'' Last week, Midway announced it had reached a $ 210 million deal with Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> to purchase routes, gates and aircraft from the strike-plagued carrier. The agreement must be approved by a federal bankruptcy court judge as part of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s strike-recovery plan to restructure into a smaller airline.
