<HEAD>Suez Launches Largest Takeover Bid Ever In France</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financiere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> says it is launching <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s biggest ever takeover bid, in a hostile offer for <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrielle </ORGANIZATION>, with which it shares control of <ORGANIZATION> Groupe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Victoire </ORGANIZATION>, a major French insurance group. The takeover proposal by <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION>, a Paris-based holding company which traces its history to the financing of the <LOCATION> Suez </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> more than a century ago, was said to be worth about $ 2.5 billion. <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> shares fell sharply in early trading today, reflecting concern that the company is in for a long, tough battle that will be costly even if it wins. The price dropped from 369 francs -LRB- $ 57.66 -RRB- per share at Tuesday's close to 347 francs -LRB- $ 54.22 -RRB- just after today's opening, but then rebounded to 355 francs -LRB- $ 55.47 -RRB- at midday. <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that if the bid is successful it will then make a tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Victoire </ORGANIZATION>'s parent company, <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financiere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Groupe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Victoire </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Paris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement that <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> is offering to pay 13,000 francs -LRB- $ 2,030 -RRB- per share for the 81.53 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrielle </ORGANIZATION> stock it does not already own. That would value the target company's total stock at 19.5 billion francs -LRB- about $ 3 billion -RRB- and the <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> offer would total 15.9 billion francs -LRB- about $ 2.5 billion -RRB-. The previous record French takeover was a bid last year by <ORGANIZATION> Schneider </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION> of about $ 930 million for control of <ORGANIZATION> Telemecanique </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electrique </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION>. But the success of the <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> bid is far from assured, with <PERSON> Jean-Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Vernes </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrielle </ORGANIZATION>, expected to put up a tough resistance. `` Suez wants a majority, and I'm categorically opposed,'' <PERSON> Vernes </PERSON> was quoted as saying in Wednesday's edition of the daily <ORGANIZATION> Le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Figaro </ORGANIZATION>. `` I made proposals for an arrangement. But if we have to go to battle, we will.'' Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> won a bruising takeover battle with Italian financier <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> for control of the huge Belgian holding company <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belgique </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Groupe </PERSON> <PERSON> Victoire </PERSON> became much more attractive after making a friendly acquisition last month of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s second-largest insurer, <ORGANIZATION> Colonia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Versicherung </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> said its bid would not affect the <LOCATION> Colonia </LOCATION> takeover. <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrielle </ORGANIZATION>'s shares were last quoted on the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> Bourse at 9,750 francs -LRB- $ 1,525 -