<HEAD>First Traders Arraigned Plead Guilty to Fraud Indictments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three commodities traders accused of cheating their customers became the first to plead guilty in the federal fraud investigation of the world's largest futures exchanges. Brothers <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Sledz </PERSON>, 29, and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sledz </PERSON>, 24, Tuesday pleaded guilty to one count each of violating the Commodities Exchange Act. The elder brother also pleaded guilty to one count of wire fraud, and the younger to one count of mail fraud. In addition, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Braniff </PERSON>, 33, pleaded guilty to two counts of violating the exchange act and two counts of mail fraud. The three men, yen traders at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, are among 46 traders indicted Aug. 2 in the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> probe of the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Published reports have said as many as 30 defendants are expected to plead guilty and cooperate with authorities. After Tuesday's court hearings, defense lawyer <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Durkin </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Sledz </LOCATION> brothers aided federal investigators by agreeing to wear recording devices to tape conversations of fellow traders. The Sledz brothers entered their pleas before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marovich </PERSON>. Additional defendants are scheduled for arraignment Wednesday. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sledz </PERSON> faces a maximum penalty of six years in prison and a $ 350,000 fine, said the brothers' attorney, <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Spevack </PERSON>. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Sledz </PERSON> could be sentenced to 10 years in prison and be fined $ 650,000. They have agreed to make restitution to customers, with the amounts to be determined later, he said. The charges in last week's indictments range from pre-arranged trading to racketeering conspiracy and tax fraud. Most allege schemes in which traders pocketed part of the profit from trades made for customers while passing their own losses on to customers. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sledz </PERSON>'s plea agreement said he executed pre-arranged trades to make money for himself and his brother, and mailed confirmation of the trades to customers in violation of exchange rules, Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Sledz </PERSON> said he executed pre-arranged trades on behalf of the <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> brokerage houses to make a profit for himself and his brother. He confirmed the trades through wire communication, <PERSON> Spevack </PERSON> said. Both acknowledged engaging in `` numerous pre-arranged trades,'' the attorney said. <ORGANIZATION> Braniff </ORGANIZATION> said in his plea agreement that he conspired with trader <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Sidel </PERSON> in July 1987 to defraud one of his customers by pre-arranging two trades for yen futures contracts. <PERSON> Sidel </PERSON> was indicted last week on charges of mail and wire fraud and violating the exchange act. <ORGANIZATION> Braniff </ORGANIZATION> also admitted to conspiring with an unidentified trader on two transactions in September 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Braniff </ORGANIZATION> faces a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison and a $ 500,000 fine. The Sledz brothers sold their trading seats at the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> in January when the first media reports of the undercover probe appeared. The three were barred from the floor of the exchange in an agreement last week with the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which oversees the exchanges, and still face disciplinary action, said <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Yemma </PERSON>. The brothers were released on $ 4,500 bond each pending sentencing, which is to be scheduled when the remaining cases against yen traders are resolved. A total of 21 traders were indicted for alleged illegal activities in the yen pit. The remaining 25 defendants traded in the Swiss franc pits at the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> and the soybean and <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond pits at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. While <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Sledz </PERSON>'s plea agreement did not name other traders, <PERSON> Spevack </PERSON> said, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sledz </PERSON> named three indicted traders with whom he engaged in pre-arranged trades _ <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Malley </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Cali </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>.
