<HEAD>Chrysler Plans Simpler Designs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A simpler car is in <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s future as consumers find themselves overwhelmed by an array of options and gadgets, the company's design chief says <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Gale </PERSON>, vice president for design at the nation's No. 3 automaker, said Tuesday that car buyers are overloaded with choices to make when buying a car or truck. `` When you look at the marketplace of the future, where we have the greatest opportunity is this whole field of back to basics,'' he said. However, he cautioned that cars ca n't look incomplete, like basic cars of the past that had obvious places for clocks or air-conditioning units. `` In a much larger sense, that's what we're struggling with on how we handle the next generation of platforms,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> will be introducing a new basic design in late 1992 for the 1993 model year. In <PERSON> Gale </PERSON>'s world of designing for the future, the cars that are built on those platforms are in the works today. `` When you get to a world where there are so many things, where there is so much technology and there's so many models, different models in different variations of those models, after a while, it's a blur,'' <PERSON> Gale </PERSON> said `` I think what the marketplace is telling us and what consumers are telling us is ` Hey, we're waiting for the guy who comes along and just says, ` Here's my <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, here's my Dodge.''' During last winter's car-show circuit, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> exhibited its Dodge Viper concept car, a two-seater stripped of a lot of the electronics that have made other cars more complex machines. Company Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> has said a decision will be made on whether to produce the Viper by early next year, and executives have said <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> should build it. However, there is concern over whether it is economically wise to build the car amid predictions of a continuing slowdown in car and truck sales and a general softening of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy. Two weeks ago, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s top 700 managers met in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> and heard <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> outline a program aimed at taking $ 1 billion out of the company's costs. Included will be a reduction in the white-collar work force by about 2,300 people, or just more than 8 percent. Company executives said no plants would be closed and product development plans would remain in place during the cost-cutting. <PERSON> Gale </PERSON> said his department was n't exempt from the cost reductions.
