<HEAD>GM Retirees Sue Automaker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of retired <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> workers have sued the automaker saying <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> reneged on health-care coverage promises. The group filed a class-action lawsuit Tuesday in federal court in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> on behalf of more than 80,000 salaried retirees, most of whom live in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. The suit said the company last year eliminated or reduced some coverage for the retirees, including chiropractic and psychiatric care, and imposed copayments and deductibles on basic health coverage. The suit seeks restoration of benefits and compensation for those who paid the deductibles and copayments. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Malloy </PERSON> said the company had no comment on the suit because it had not had time to study it. `` <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said we would have these benefits for our lifetimes,'' said <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Moeller </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Fenton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION> `` I felt we had a moral and legal contract. `` They ca n't take it away now,'' said <PERSON> Moeller </PERSON>, an accountant who retired in 1982. <PERSON> Malloy </PERSON> said all salaried <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> workers should have known that their health care benefits could change. She said last year's changes were made to encourage active and retired employees to switch to more economical health care plans, such as health maintenance organizations. Currently, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> salaried workers have to pay the first $ 200 of medical costs annually and 20 percent of other costs with a $ 500 ceiling. Thus, a worker could spend up to $ 700 a year for health care. The family limit is $ 750 a year. `` We are all on fixed incomes and we are all at a state in our lives when we truly need all of the health benefits that <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> promised us during our working years,'' <PERSON> Moeller </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Moeller </PERSON> said the suit was filed in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> because a retiree group is active there and that <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> may have too much influence if the case was filed in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>.
