<HEAD>United Finds Crack in Fourth 727-100</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> has found a small crack in a fourth <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727-100 jetliner since the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> ordered an industry-wide inspection in July. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday that to date, cracks have been found in the metallic skins of four <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> 727s and one <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> 727. The cracks ranged in size from 20 inches to less than half an inch. Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's second-largest airline, previously reported finding cracks in three planes. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> is considering whether to order continuing inspections of the 31 oldest 727s registered in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said agency spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Duff </PERSON>. The inspections might also be broadened to include somewhat newer 727-100s as well, he said. The cracks, first discovered on <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> jets, occur on the seam that joins the upper and lower parts of the fuselage. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> modified the way the seam was joined after building the first 46 727s, increasing the thickness of the splice by inserting a spacer piece of metal between the overlapping fuselage sections. `` We had never seen cracking along the lower rivet row -LRB- at the splice -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> said. `` This was something new.'' Though the cracks' safety implication is not fully understood, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> issued an emergency directive ordering airlines to inspect the aging 727s for the fuselage cracks, and not to fly the planes until they were inspected and any cracks repaired. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> and American planes have been repaired and are back in service. Each of the planes had accumulated 46,000 to 49,000 flights. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> had billed the planes as having a design life cycle of 20 years and 60,000 flights, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> still believes the planes can fly indefinitely with proper maintenance, <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said.
