<SECOND>BC-Credit Fraud-Tips, Adv 13,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release Sunday, Aug. 13 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tips For Traveling With Credit Cards, Travelers Checks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Credit Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are a few financial safety tips for travelers, according to industry experts and consumer groups:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ Keep most of your money in travelers checks They're safer than cash because the issuer gives full or partial refunds for lost or stolen checks. Checks in foreign currency may be available at a major bank at official exchange rates, usually without service fees. _ Carry <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollars and the currency of whatever country you're <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> money should be in small denominations to handle minor expenses, such as tips or parking, before or after departure. _ Bring at least one major credit card for either identification or purchases Two is better, since not all cards are universally accepted, but leave the cards you do n't expect to use at home. _ Try to buy all your travel tickets through a credit card, if possible It's often easier to get replacement tickets and many credit-card companies provide limited travel insurance. _ After charging meals, souvenirs or other items destroy all charge card carbons immediately _ Double check your credit card bill to ensure all purchases are listed correctly, and contact your bank or credit-card company immediately if there's an incorrect expense Cardholders are liable for up to $ 50 of unauthorized purchases before they report a card stolen or lost but they're not liable for any purchases after a report is filed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance Sunday, Aug. 13</NOTE>
