<HEAD>Target Of Largest French Takeover Bid Promises Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrielle </ORGANIZATION> will resist the largest takeover bid ever attempted in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, a $ 2.5 billion offer from a former ally, its president said Wednesday. <PERSON> Jean-Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Vernes </PERSON>, head of the holding company under attack from <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financiere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION>, a Paris-based bank holding company, declined to discuss what allies he might be lining up for the fight. <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> won a long and difficult takeover battle last year with Italian financier <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> for control of the huge Belgian holding company <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belgique </ORGANIZATION>. The prize in the takeover battle is <PERSON> Groupe </PERSON> <PERSON> Victoire </PERSON>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s second-biggest insurance group <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION>, which traces its corporate history to the financing of the <LOCATION> Suez </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> more than a century ago, currently shares control of <ORGANIZATION> Groupe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Victoire </ORGANIZATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrielle </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Paris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement that <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> proposes to offer the equivalent of $ 2,030 per share for the 81.5 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrielle </ORGANIZATION> stock it does not already own. That would value the target company's equity at $ 3 billion and the <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> offer would total about $ 2.5 billion. <PERSON> Vernes </PERSON> was quoted by the French news agency <ORGANIZATION> Agence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> France-Presse </ORGANIZATION> as saying he would make no statement until the hostile takeover bid by <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> has been approved by stock market regulatory authorities. The regulatory decision is expected on Aug. 18, and if the bid is approved, stockholders then would have a month to decide whether to sell at that price. Trading in <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrielle </ORGANIZATION> stock has been frozen since Friday. It was last quoted on the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> Bourse at the equivalent of $ 1,525 per share. The price of <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> shares fell to $ 55.55 a share from $ 57.66 on Wednesday in active trading. <PERSON> Groupe </PERSON> <PERSON> Victoire </PERSON> was originally part of the <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> holdings, but when it appeared likely that the Socialists would win the 1981 elections, <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION>'s president at the time, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Frances </PERSON>, quietly transferred control to the holding company <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrielle </ORGANIZATION>, which he controlled along with allies including the <PERSON> Dassault </PERSON> family. When the new Socialist government indeed nationalized <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> along with other banks and industrial firms, it was surprised to find the Groupe Victoire insurance company no longer a <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, although <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> did retain a minority interest _ partly direct and partly through <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrielle </ORGANIZATION>. The conservative government elected in 1986 sold <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> to private investors, but its new owners have had uneasy relations with <PERSON> Vernes </PERSON>, who succeeded <PERSON> Frances </PERSON> as head of <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrielle </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> said if its takeover bid is successful, it will then make a tender offer for the <ORGANIZATION> Victoire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> company </ORGANIZATION>'s parent, <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financiere </ORGANIZATION> du <ORGANIZATION> Groupe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Victoire </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> already owns 30 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Groupe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Victoire </ORGANIZATION>, but apparently is unhappy as simply a silent investor. <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> also owns 18.47 percent of the shares of <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrielle </ORGANIZATION>, which has 40 percent of the capital and 48 percent of the voting rights of <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financiere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Groupe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Victoire </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Groupe </PERSON> <PERSON> Victoire </PERSON> became much more attractive after making a friendly acquisition last month of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s second-largest insurer, <ORGANIZATION> Colonia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Versicherung </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> said its bid would not affect the <LOCATION> Colonia </LOCATION> takeover. <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement that its bid for <ORGANIZATION> Victoire </ORGANIZATION> was part of its preparation for the dropping of barriers within the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> after 1992. Reports in several French newspapers Wednesday said <PERSON> Vernes </PERSON> would likely line up support from the <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> group of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> to help fight off the <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> takeover bid. <PERSON> Vernes </PERSON> is also president of Beghin-Say, a French paper-making unit of <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Vernes </PERSON> declined to comment on the reports that <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> would be involved. Under French stock market regulations, any competing bid for <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrielle </ORGANIZATION>, either by <PERSON> Vernes </PERSON> allies or others, would have to be at least 5 percent higher than the <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> tender offer. The main asset of <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrielle </ORGANIZATION> is its controlling stake in <ORGANIZATION> Groupe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Victoire </ORGANIZATION>. It also has some real estate and minority industrial holdings.
