<FIRST>s f BC-PersonalFile-Guerrero Adv13 1stLd-Writethru 08-09 0934</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Guerrero, Adv 13, 1st Ld-Writethru,0959</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Aug. 13 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Youth Takes Charge At Madrid Stock Exchange, Leads `El Big Bang'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to fix garble</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCISCO CONDE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans know <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON> as a $ 2 million-a-year slugger who can wallop a baseball, but in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s financial world the name refers to someone known for a different kind of big bang That <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON> is a lawyer, securities professional and son of a Spanish banker. Last month he was elected chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Madrid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> at age 36, making him the youngest person to head a major securities market. More importantly, <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON> has been presiding over a profound reform in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s securities industry that's shattered the 160-year-old shackles of government control, a revolution known as `` El Big Bang.'' It officially began July 29, when the state monopoly on securities trading ended. Stock exchanges became private businesses. Government-appointed stockbrokers were replaced by private brokerages. After a transition period, once-fixed commissions will be freely negotiatable. Like the `` Big Bang'' deregulation of the British markets a few years ago, the Spanish securities overhaul is aimed at making stock trading more competitive, efficient and attractive to foreigners seeking opportunities in one of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s fastest-growing economies. `` The changeover has gone very well, although we've still got a long road to run,'' <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON> said in an interview. `` Many people, especially in the business press, did not believe we would be ready by the July 29 deadline, but we were.'' He's not related to the Dominican-born <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON> who bats cleanup for the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cardinals </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. But their aggressiveness is strikingly similar. <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON>'s management of the El Big Bang changeover at <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>'s stock exchange, where 70 percent of Spanish stocks are traded, has overshadowed his conspicuous youth in a profession historically dominated by rigid thinking and slow-moving brokers accustomed to the life of government bureaucrats `` He talks about selling products and services,'' said <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunez-Lagos </PERSON>, 67, a 38-year career stockbroker and president of the Hispano brokerage. `` This is precisely the difference between the old exchange and the new one.'' <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON> smokes heavily and wears modest clothes that belie his wealth. He made a fortune channeling investment funds from foreign markets into <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> through the <LOCATION> Asesores </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bursatiles </LOCATION> brokerage, which he helped found. In 1988, Asesores accounted for more than 5 percent of total volume on the <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> exchange, 80 percent of that from foreign investors. His youth stands in marked contrast to other world stock exchange leaders. <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> is 58, for example. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> is 58. <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Caty </PERSON> is 48. <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Minoru </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagaoka </PERSON> is 65. <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON> attributed his election by the revamped stock exchange's 51 members partly to what he called an across-the-board generational change in Spanish society. He mentioned <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Croissier </PERSON>, 38, named president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, the government agency that will police the markets under the reform. Prime Minister <PERSON> Felipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> is only 47, <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON> noted. `` In other places where there has been a long, stable history and much tradition, my election might not have been possible,'' <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON> said. `` But I'm a firm believer in putting younger people in important posts.'' <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON> said his priorities include revising the cumbersome time-consuming system for finalizing stock trades and developing the nation's first stock-options market. Options, widely traded by speculators in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, are rights to buy or sell stocks within a set time for a set price. He also intends to expand computerized trading, introduced in April using a model of the <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s Computer Automated Trading System. The Spanish CATS network links the <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> exchange to smaller exchanges in <LOCATION> Barcelona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bilbao </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Valencia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON> said 22 percent of all trading is now done via CATS and the figure should double by the end of the year, as the historical open-outcry system of traders shouting bids gradually is phased out. His fast rise in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s securities industry reflects <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON>'s own intense drive and ambition He placed first seven years ago in the tough state exams for his stockbroker's diploma. But he was never completely satisfied just peddling stocks and looked for other opportunities. In 1984, he and two friends visited financial institutions in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to discuss their preparations for <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s market deregulation. That's where he got the idea for what became an immensely successful business in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. `` They all wanted to hear about Spanish investment possibilities,'' <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON> said. `` They said if there was a firm in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> that could provide top-quality research and services, it would get all the clients it could handle and more.'' <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON> and friends returned to <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> and formed <LOCATION> Asesores </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bursatiles </LOCATION>. In 1985, the firm channeled about $ 350 million in foreign investments into the Spanish markets. Last year they handled $ 3.8 billion, mainly in foreign money, and have since diversified the firm into other corporate financial services. Asked if he was concerned that <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s market deregulation would incite rampant greed and fraud, <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON> said he believed the government could still police the securities industry. `` I'm completely confident that the new <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> is going to strongly discourage this and be very tough on rule-breakers,'' he said. As an example, he mentioned the commission's recent probe of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s Spanish subsidiary. Even before any formal action was taken, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> shut down the operation July 17 after determining it had improperly sold securities in a Spanish oil company.
</TEXT>
