<FIRST>r f AM-USBorrowing     08-09 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US Borrowing,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Increased S&amp;L Borrowing Seen Threatening U.S. Future</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-S&amp;Ls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities will have to borrow tens of billions of dollars from other countries to help bail out failed savings and loans institutions, dollars foreigners will someday use to compete for scarcer goods in this country, an economist predicted Wednesday. The bill President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> signed Wednesday authorizes borrowing $ 50 billion over the next 26 months. The total cost of the bailout will be far higher because of interest costs. Foreigners already buy future claims on this country at a rate of $ 10 billion a month through their purchases of American bonds, shares, real estate and other property. Americans do not save enough of their own money to pay for the things they want from foreigners now, so the needed money has to be lent to this country from abroad. `` Unfortunately, people in government focus on short-term problems and not on the long term,'' said <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Canzoneri </PERSON>, professor of economics at <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` I'm a baby-boomer. In the long run, there'll be fewer people in this country to produce goods to support me in my old age. The same is true of Mr. <PERSON> Yamaguchi </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> _ and the Japanese population is getting older faster than ours is.'' <PERSON> Canzoneri </PERSON> sees Japanese and other foreigners wanting to cash in their loans and investments and use the dollars to buy up <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> goods at a time when fewer American goods will be produced in proportion to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> population. All that money chasing fewer goods will run up prices, lower living standards and bring pressures to cut pensions in this country, he predicted. <PERSON> Canzoneri </PERSON> also predicts additional government borrowing will cause short-term problems. `` Lenders in Wall Street may get jittery,'' he said. `` That would drive up interest rates. That will increase the cost of the federal government's deficit. Then there would be pressure on the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> to push interest rates down. That would mean even more borrowing and the threat of inflation.''
</TEXT>
