<FIRST>r f AM-ChickenStudy     08-09 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicken Study,0381</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Col. Sanders Meets Fourier's Law As Student Researches Chicken
Formula</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Norris </PERSON> is in search of the perfectly cooked chicken, but his tools are more likely to include a slide rule than a spatula. <PERSON> Norris </PERSON>, a 26-year-old graduate chemical engineering student at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louisville </ORGANIZATION>, is trying to create a mathematical model for showing how quickly chicken pieces will cook under varying conditions. Financed by a $ 15,000 grant from <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fried </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicken </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Norris </PERSON> is attempting to develop the model for his masters thesis at the Equipment Performance Lab of the company's Col. <ORGANIZATION> Sanders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. `` Basically all cooking is a physical phenomenon,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Mohan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rao </PERSON>, a senior research scientist for <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fried </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicken </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's biggest fried chicken chain. With <PERSON> Norris </PERSON>' model, `` we should be able to tell exactly what the process should be,'' he said. Whenever the company changes its brand of shortening or uses a new type of pressure cooker, it has to alter the cooking procedure. The company would use the formula being developed by <PERSON> Norris </PERSON> to replace trial and error testing methods. `` Minor improvements in productivity translate into a significant amount of money,'' says <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Detwiler </PERSON>, a spokesman at <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fried </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicken </ORGANIZATION>, which sells nearly $ 6 billion worth of chicken and other foods annually. Using an overhead projector, <PERSON> Norris </PERSON> creates graph outlines of drumsticks measured in two positions to arrive at an average dimension. Then, with what <PERSON> Norris </PERSON> says is best explained as <PERSON> Fourier </PERSON>'s Law, he uses the measurements to work out an equation that will predict how quickly various parts of the chicken will cook. <PERSON> Fourier </PERSON>'s Law states that with two masses, `` the greater the temperature difference, the faster the heat transfers,'' <PERSON> Rao </PERSON> said. The 40-year-old <PERSON> Rao </PERSON> spent 15 years as a professor of food processing at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>. Last month, he was named an adjunct professor at the university, where he will teach a class on food processing next spring. <PERSON> Norris </PERSON> said he had no `` particular interest in working with chicken'' before he was selected for the project. However, standing in a room surrounded by trays of fried chicken, <PERSON> Norris </PERSON> said he might consider a career in food-process control.
</TEXT>
