<HEAD>Board Chairman Defends Decision on Soybeans; Pledges `Clean House'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Commodities Probe, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> will do whatever it takes to restore confidence after 46 traders were indicted as a result of a sweeping federal probe of trading fraud, the exchange chairman pledged Wednesday. `` We do not tolerate a single customer being abused on our exchange,'' board Chairman <PERSON> Karsten </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> told the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Feed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grains </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which ended its three-day session Wednesday. `` We want your confidence. We will do anything and everything to keep it.'' <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> told council members the board has increased its audit and investigation staff by 30 percent, and on Thursday will consider a proposal to increase the penalty for each rule violation to $ 250,000 from $ 75,000. `` That's how bad they want a clean house,'' he said of the tougher policies, which followed last week's indictment of dozens of traders at the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> also defended the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> decision to order the sale of some July soybean contracts as `` a last resort'' to keep the market operating smoothly. But farmer <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kintzle </PERSON> of Coggon, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, said there still are too many unanswered questions about the soybean sale, which primarily affected an Italian processor, <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finanziaria </ORGANIZATION> SpA. `` I think the the <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> deal is bothering the farmers in gravel-road <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> even more than the indictments,'' <PERSON> Kintzle </PERSON> said. `` If they had left the market run, we'd have had $ 8 or $ 9 beans. Farmers might not have sold but at least they would have had the opportunity.'' The Board of Trade move was widely interpreted as an effort to break up an attempt to corner the market. <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> denied that was its aim, saying it needed the beans for its crushing operation and customers. The action forced <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> to give up nearly all of its July contracts for the delivery of 23 million bushels of soybeans. The <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> already had taken steps to cancel an exemption that allowed <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> to hold contracts for more than the 3 million-bushel limit. The federal agency has said there were contracts for delivery of about 40 million bushels of soybeans and only about 12 million bushels available. <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> preferred to apply its liquidation order `` across the marketplace,'' to everyone with more than 3 million bushels, whether they were buyers or sellers. The order required people to liquidate 20 percent of their contracts each day, and to have contracts for no more than 1 million bushels of beans on July 20, he said. The <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> plan would have forced <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> to liquidate contracts for 20 million bushels in one day, <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> said. `` That would have had long-lasting, devastating consequences on the soybean complex,'' he said. `` I would n't have wanted to speculate on where prices would have gone.'' But farmer <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Wentworth </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Oreana </LOCATION>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, was uneasy about the move. `` I have some concerns that it affected the credibility of the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, and some farmers still have problems with that,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Feed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grains </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, a private organization of farm and agribusiness groups, was formed in 1960 to promote export markets for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn, barley and sorghum.
