<HEAD>Price of Citrus Land Heating Up in Recovery from Freezes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The value of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> citrus land is rising, reflecting a general improvement in the agricultural economy and a comeback from winter freezes, according to a new survey. The value of mature <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> orange groves was up 8.2 percent to $ 11,873 an acre, and <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> orange acreage rose 5.4 percent to $ 11,800 an acre in the survey period from November 1988 to May 1989. The survey, released this week by the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, demonstrated the confidence and optimism in the heart of the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> citrus belt, hard-hit by severe freezes in December 1983 and January 1985 that killed nearly 200,000 acres of trees `` We've seen prices bottom out and they're on the way back up,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, citrus specialist with the <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Extension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Relatively mild weather has prevailed during the past four winters and citrus planting has been active. About 125,000 acres were planted statewide in 1986 and 1987, industry figures show. The value of an acre of mature grapefruit groves in central <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> was placed at $ 10,265 an acre, a 5.5 percent jump from November 1988. In <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, grapefruit groves were valued at $ 10,420 an acre, a 2.7 percent increase. Part of the value of the farmland reflects its potential for commercial development, said the authors of the report, <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> agriculture professors <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> and visiting professor J.H. <PERSON> Atkinson </PERSON>. They said caution must be used in making year-to-year comparisons from prior surveys.
