<HEAD>EEC Posts 1.1 Percent Growth in 1st Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> economy grew by 1.2 percent during the first quarter of 1989, <ORGANIZATION> Eurostat </ORGANIZATION>, the statistics agency of the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Copmmunity </ORGANIZATION> reported Wednesday. It said this was the highest quarterly rate since the third quarter of 1987. By comparison, <ORGANIZATION> Eurostat </ORGANIZATION> said, the economies of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> _ the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s main trading partners _ rose by 1.1 and 2.2 percent respectively during the first quarter. <ORGANIZATION> Eurostat </ORGANIZATION> said the first three months of 1989 saw a 4.4 percent jump in investments, the highest in four years and well above the 1 percent growth rate of the last quarter of 1988. EEC exports grew by 3.7 percent, up from 1.6 percent during the previous quarter. Imports rose by 1.3 percent, down from 3.2 percent during the last three months of 1988. <ORGANIZATION> Eurostat </ORGANIZATION> said first-quarter growth in private consumption slowed to 0.5 percent from 0.6 percent during 1988's fourth quarter. At 2.9 percent, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> posted the strongest economic growth during the first quarter. It was followed by <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> -LRB- 1.1 percent -RRB- and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, -LRB- 0.7 percent -RRB-, <ORGANIZATION> Eurostat </ORGANIZATION> said. The British economy was the weakest with a drop in output of 0.4 percent, <ORGANIZATION> Eurostat </ORGANIZATION> said.
