<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 2058EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f AM-GasolinePrices Adv13   08-09 0964</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gasoline Prices, Adv 13,0994</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Aug. 13</HEAD>
<HEAD>Whatever Happened to the Summer '89 Gas Shortage?</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Brimming storage tanks of gasoline that should be almost empty are teaching oil companies an old economics lesson this summer: When prices rise, consumers buy less. The cost of gasoline, which soared 20 cents or more this spring in the aftermath of the Exxon Valdez oil spill and widespread predictions of shortages, has been stabilizing and even dropping in some places because of a surprising oversupply at the height of the driving season. `` Major oil companies expected people were more indifferent to prices than they actually turned out to be,'' says <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Veno </PERSON>, director of oil market analysis for <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, an economic research concern. `` They would n't have wanted to raise prices so much as to undermine demand and they've tended to do that.'' Not only are motorists making fewer trips to the filling station, they're also buying cheaper grades of gasoline, industry statistics suggest. The result is that instead of shortages there are surpluses, especially of high-priced high-octane premium. That does n't mean demand could n't pick up _ there's still a good month's worth of summer vacation season left. More gasoline consumption could alter the supply-demand equation and prices could start rising. But as of late last month, the average retail price for all types of gasoline had dropped to $ 1.13 a gallon from a peak $ 1.18 a gallon on May 19, according to statistics from the <ORGANIZATION> Lundberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Survey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a research group that tracks gasoline prices nationwide. The <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, which monitors the inflation rate, estimates the average price per gallon for all grades of motor fuel soared from 94.4 cents in January to $ 1.15 in June, a 22 percent gain. High octane, which averaged about $ 1.09 in January, rose 19 cents to $ 1.28 a gallon in June. Unleaded regular, the most widely consumed grade, rose from about 92 cents a gallon to $ 1.11. `` When prices of gasoline went up people bought less but more important they started buying cheaper grades,'' says <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Eklof </PERSON>, an energy specialist with the consulting group <ORGANIZATION> Cambridge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>. `` When the customer switches and downgrades it increases the overall supply in total.'' Petroleum Intelligence Weekly, an industry trade publication, reported recently that premium unleaded sales have fallen at least 10 percent because of motorists switching to regular unleaded. Wholesale prices are down even more sharply than retail, in some cases below levels last seen two years ago. That could translate into even lower retail prices in coming months. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> price of wholesale regular unleaded, for example, fell from 78 cents a gallon in late April to about 51 cents a gallon earlier this month. Overestimates of summer driving and concern about supply disruptions caused by the Exxon oil spill led refiners to make too much gasoline, analysts say. `` What happened is that people altered their plans,'' says <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Crosby </PERSON>, executive director of the Service Station Dealers of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>. `` So the big usage did n't materialize and now we have a glut of refined product on the market. If the price falls that much it has to be a tremendous oversupply.'' Predictions of shortages arose from a number of other causes. Tougher federal antipollution regulations, for example, require refineries to use more crude in making gasoline. Refinery accidents, maintenance delays, and lower production from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> fields also played a role But the biggest shot to the market psyche was the Exxon oil spill. The March 24 disaster in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> jolted the market because the cleanup temporarily disrupted the flow of crude to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> refiners, raising the possibility of shortages. Refiners responded by reducing sales to customers. Almost overnight, prices rocketed, with wholesale premium gasoline up 30 cents in some parts of the country. In <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, for example, regular unleaded surged to $ 1.07 on April 5 from 74 cents the day of the spill. The price shock quickly rippled through the country. In the end, shipments from <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> were disrupted for days instead of weeks. About 13 million barrels of southbound crude was delayed, in addition to the 250,000 barrels lost from the leaking <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> tanker. Moreover, refinery repairs and accidents had not caused other delays anticipated earlier. Refinery capacity turned out to be greater than expected and refiners were better prepared to handle the new antipollution requirements. After the spill, crude oil prices stabilized in the $ 19 - $ 20-a-barrel range until last month, when they slid to about $ 18 in response to the softening gasoline market and a surge in summer production by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries Refiners are just starting to slow production while the surplus dwindles. But that means crude oil stockpiles are growing. `` It's a double-edged sword. If refiners do n't cut back there's too much product If they do then there is too much crude,'' says <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fiedler </PERSON>, energy analyst at <ORGANIZATION> E.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Man </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Whether late-summer vacationers will reduce the oversupply of gasoline remains unclear. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which tracks summer driving, had predicted a 4 percent increase this year over last but now says that growth is unlikely. `` It is fair to say that gasoline prices have had an impact on gasoline consumption and driving habits as well,'' says <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheske </PERSON>, spokesman for AAA. `` Whether people canceled vacations I do n't think so. They're just more conservative in their driving habits.'' Some analysts believe consumers have sent a clear message to oil companies. `` The lesson oil companies are learning is that you ca n't go and raise prices by 20 percent and not expect something to happen,'' <PERSON> Veno </PERSON> says. `` It's a big lesson.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday Aug. 13</NOTE>
