<HEAD>Corn Prices Lower, Soybeans, Wheat Climb Before USDA Crop Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Corn futures were lower, but soybeans and wheat prices finished higher Wednesday as traders hewed to narrow ranges in advance of a much-anticipated <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> survey of crop production for the year. On other markets, sugar futures surged on rumors that <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> was in the market for as many as 300,000 tons; heating oil led a modest run-up in the petroleum futures complex; and frozen pork belly prices continued sliding in the face of historically high inventories. Corn came under pressure with the opening bell at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> because of the unusually high crop production estimate _ 7.72 billion bushels _ released after the close of trading Tuesday by influential private forecaster <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON> <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON>. Although <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON>'s forecast for soybeans was high as well _ 1.95 billion bushels _ most traders apparently felt that was discounted during the late wave of selling Tuesday that dragged November soybeans to yet another contract low. Traders tested the contract low at $ 5.62 again early Wednesday. After support held above that mark, many traders squared up their positions and headed to the sidelines to await Thursday's government report `` The confusion between <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON>'s numbers and what the traders were looking for pulled the market the past two days,'' said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gidel </PERSON>, research director for <ORGANIZATION> LIT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` I think people were happy just to even up and wait and see what the official numbers look like.'' Wheat settled 1 -LCB- cents to 5 cents higher, with the contract for delivery in September at $ 3.95 a bushel; corn was -LCB- cent to 2 cents lower, with September at $ 2.23 a bushel; oats were 1 \ cents lower to unchanged, with September at $ 1.36 a bushel; soybeans were 1 -LCB- cents to 9 cents higher, with August at $ 5.94 a bushel Rumors of a big purchase by <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, which some traders speculated may already have taken place, pushed sugar futures prices above 14 cents a pound at mid-session. `` That number has psychological value and it got some people excited enough to jump on the bandwagon,'' said <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` Sugar supplies have been tight for a while and a report of somebody coming in and taking that much out of the market was bound to spur a rally.'' Late profit-taking helped trim the gains, however, and sugar finished .05 cent to .26 cent higher on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coffee </ORGANIZATION>, Sugar and <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, with October at 14.07 cents. An <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> report released after Tuesday's trading showed a substantial drawdown in heating oil supplies last month and that lifted the entire complex Crude oil was 9 cents to 14 cents higher at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, with September at $ 18.21 a barrel; heating oil was .66 cent to .96 cent higher, with September at 49.43 cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline was .14 cent to .40 cent higher, with September at 50.58 cents a gallon. Livestock futures were mostly lower, while pork futures were sharply lower at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .35 cent lower to .27 cent higher, with August at 74.57 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .33 cent higher, with August at 84.90 cents a pound; live hogs were .33 cent to 1.23 cents lower, with August at 46.77 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .30 cent to 1.13 cents higher, with August at 24.92 cents a pound. Precious metals were mixed. Gold prices climbed 10 cents to 70 cents on the Comex, with August at $ 366.90 a troy ounce; silver slipped 1 cent to 3 cents, with August at 515.5 cents. Platinum, traded on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION>, was $ 1 to $ 1.80 lower, with September at $ 484.70 a troy ounce.
