<FIRST>r f AM-BallyRefinancing     08-09 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bally Refinancing,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Casino Commission Approves $350 Million Debt Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MARTELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Bally </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> can begin a $ 350 million debt refinancing to be paid for largely through its Park Place Casino in <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, state regulators ruled Wednesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Casino </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> rejected arguments from state gaming officials that the refinancing would put Park Place, one of <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s leading gaming halls, on shaky financial footing. `` I find that this is a responsible proposal which will not jeopardize Park Place's financial stability or its ability to maintain a first-class facility,'' commission chairman <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Read </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Bally </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION>, the casino's Chicago-based parent company, wants to make Park Place more independent. The refinancing plan includes offering $ 350 million in mortgage notes to fund a $ 150 million dividend payment to <ORGANIZATION> Bally </ORGANIZATION> and retire existing corporate debt. The casino would incur the $ 350 million debt. About $ 120 million would be used by the parent firm to retire debt unrelated to <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> ventures. Read admitted the proposal would increase Park Place's debt without an equal benefit to the casino. But he said he is `` satisfied that the proposed transaction is responsible and is not a plan to siphon funds from a healthy facility and leave it in a weakened state. Nor does it mark the beginning of a withdrawal by -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Bally </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- from the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> gaming market.'' Read said <ORGANIZATION> Bally </ORGANIZATION> has invested more than $ 600 million in Park P