<HEAD>Brazil Denies Moratorium On Interest Payments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Finance Minister <PERSON> Mailson </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Nobrega </PERSON> said Wednesday the nation's foreign creditors have agreed to a delay in debt payments and he denied <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> will enter a moratorium. <PERSON> Da </PERSON> <PERSON> Nobrega </PERSON> told the congressional <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> that the government wanted to avoid a confrontation with creditors and wished to `` negotiate lateness'' until the country's foreign reserves reached a `` respectable level.'' In July, the government restricted the outflow of dollars by channeling all foreign exchange operations through the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, equivalent to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>. Since then, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s cash reserves have risen nearly $ 1 billion to $ 6.5 billion, surpassing the minimum level considered safe by the government, which is $ 6 billion, equivalent to four months of imports. But the government continues to hold back about $ 1 billion in debt payments since June 30, including $ 400 million to Western government leaders due July 3 and some $ 600 million in interest payments and dividend remittances by foreign multinationals, <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Nobrega </PERSON> said. That falls short of a moratorium, which would be a total halt to payments on foreign debt. <PERSON> Da </PERSON> <PERSON> Nobrega </PERSON> said the government needed the reserves to avoid shocks from abroad and insure a smooth transition of government during the coming months. On Nov. 15, Brazilians will elect President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>'s successor in the nation's first people's vote in 29 years The winner will take office on Mar. 15, 1990. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, tottering under a $ 112 billion foreign debt, the Third World's largest, is also seeking fresh money to meet an interest payment of $ 3 billion due in September to private foreign banks. The government is negotiating an agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> that would allow <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> to receive $ 4 billion in fresh loans withheld by private banks and lending organizations. Creditors have balked at lending more money to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, which has not controlled an annual inflation rate of 1,000 percent, monetary expansion and a soaring public defecit. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s public deficit, running at around 7 percent of GNP this year, is one of the principal generators of inflation.
