<HEAD>Congressional Economists Say Budget Cuts Will Aid Trade Deficit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `The congressional ...,' to RESTORE dropped letter
``b'' in the word ``billion.'' ^Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Slashing the federal budget deficit would dramatically improve the nation's $ 129 billion annual trade imbalance, congressional fiscal experts said Wednesday. The non-partisan <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said that by meeting the deficit targets mandated by the Gramm-Rudman law _ which requires a balanced federal budget by 1993 _ the country's trade shortfall could be cut by $ 40 billion to $ 65 billion Many economists agree that reducing federal red ink would help the trade imbalance. But by producing its 77-page report, which relies on simulations to make its arguments, <ORGANIZATION> CBO </ORGANIZATION> provided more ammunition to members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> pressing for a fiscal 1991 budget deal with the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> that would entail major deficit cuts. The congressional agency estimated that eventually, every $ 1 billion cut in the federal deficit would improve the nation's trade picture by $ 300 million to $ 500 million. The <ORGANIZATION> CBO </ORGANIZATION> also said that expanding the money supply would have little effect on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit, since exchange rates are flexible. `` Among the options policymakers have for reducing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> current account deficit, reducing the federal budget deficit ... is the most promising,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CBO </ORGANIZATION> said. The current account deficit is the broadest measure of the trade deficit, registering not only products but services as well. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> current account deficit reached $ 132 billion last year and is expected to be about $ 129 billion this year. At the beginning of this decade, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had a slight surplus in trade. To pay for the extra goods and services entering this country, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must borrow money from abroad. `` In the long run, this borrowing will transfer wealth abroad and this will reduce living standards of Americans in the future,'' <ORGANIZATION> CBO </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reischauer </PERSON> said at a news conference. Economists disagree over how threatening the trade imbalance is. Some say it bodes ill because it could trigger protectionist legislation and recession, while others argue it means little. But they mostly agree that cutting the federal deficit would ease the trade shortfall by lowering the need to borrow from abroad, reducing interest rates, allowing the dollar to decline and thus making American products more attractive to foreign buyers. The budget deficit for fiscal 1989 _ which ends Sept. 30 _ is expected to be about $ 148 billion. The Gramm-Rudman law's deficit ceiling for next year is $ 100 billion, and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will resume its efforts to reach that target when it returns from its summer recess in September. <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON>, D-Calif., said the <ORGANIZATION> CBO </ORGANIZATION> conclusions `` emphasize the urgency of agreeing upon a bold deficit reduction package for fiscal year 1991 as soon as possible.
