<HEAD>Appeals Court Vacates Favorable Pickens Ruling In Phillips Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court Wednesday set aside a decision clearing corporate raider <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boone </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON>' investment group of violating securities and racketeering laws in a takeover bid for <ORGANIZATION> Phillips </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> five years ago. A three-judge panel of the 3rd <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> vacated a lower court's summary judgment in favor of <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON>' <ORGANIZATION> Mesa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partnership </ORGANIZATION> and sent the case back to <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>. The lawsuits brought by <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> shareholders accused <ORGANIZATION> Mesa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> deception </ORGANIZATION> in its $ 9.1 billion attempt to take over the <LOCATION> Bartelsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, oil giant. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>, an attorney for <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION>, said from <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Del. </LOCATION>, that he had not seen the decision and would not comment. The court ruled a jury could reasonably conclude that <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION>, which made $ 89 million on the takeover attempt, had always intended to sell its <LOCATION> Phillips </LOCATION> stock back to the company for a better deal than the other stockholders received. Such a tactic is known as `` greenmail.'' During the takeover attempt, <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> repeatedly said <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION> would not consider selling back its shares unless the same deal was offered to all stockholders. The partnership changed its stance when <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> adopted a `` poison pill'' strategy to fight the takeover. The appeals court said the district court incorrectly cited a lack of evidence. Although much of the evidence was circumstantial, Circuit Judge <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scirica </PERSON> wrote, no other type normally is available in bad-faith cases. `` A jury could reasonably conclude that the partnership either was reckless in making the equal-basis statements given the forseeability of what actually occurred or that the partnership intended from the outset of its tender offer to sell back to <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> on an unequal basis,'' <PERSON> Scirica </PERSON> wrote. The appeals panel upheld the summary judgment involving all <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> state charges.
